(28, 'How to Use A Japanese Air Conditioner', 'Mastering the functions of your a/c remote is key to surviving in Japan.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', NULL, '<p>During my first <span style=\"color:#ff0000\">winter in Japan</span>, my faithful A/C had kept my room at a cozy temperature. But upon turning the A/C on in the summer, I only seemed to feel more sweaty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Resisting the urge to button mash, I looked closely at the air-conditioner&rsquo;s remote control. The A/C had been set to &ldquo;heat.&rdquo; With a simple press of the button, I changed the setting to &ldquo;cool,&rdquo; and the room was flooded with glorious chilly air.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a performance to rival the &ldquo;2001: A Space Odessey&rdquo; monkeys, I raised the remote above my head and brought it down on the standard-issue <span style=\"color:#ff0000\">Leopalace apartment table</span>&nbsp;several times while screeching.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You too can have a moment of triumph such as this by using this basic guide on how to use your Japanese air-conditioner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>How to use a Japanese air-conditioner</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Japanese, the air-conditioning unit itself is called &ldquo;air-con&rdquo; (エアコン), and the remote control is called &ldquo;rimo-con&rdquo; (リモコン). If you have a <span style=\"color:#ff0000\">furnished apartment</span> and can&rsquo;t find the remote control, it might be mounted on the wall near the air-conditioner, perhaps hidden behind the curtain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most remote controls have the same basic functions so I will be using my own remote control as an example. The buttons may not be in the same place, so take a close look at the kanji. Some higher-end air-conditioners may have additional functions not covered in this guide, such as an on-off timer (タイマー), self-cleaning setting (内部クリーン), or clothes drying setting (衣類乾燥).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"border:0px solid black; height:966px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; margin-top:0px; width:690px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Using a Japanese air-conditioner remote control</h2>\r\n\r\n<h4>On/Off = 運転/停止</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Obviously, the most important button on a Japanese A/C remote control is the &ldquo;on/off&rdquo; button. The on/off button is labeled 運転/停止 (pronounced &ldquo;<em>unten/teishi</em>&rdquo; and literally meaning &ldquo;operation/suspension&rdquo;). Sometimes this button will be labeled 運転切/入 or just 切/入. Press this button once and the A/C will come on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once the A/C is on, the little screen on the remote control will also come on. The temperature will be displayed, possibly along with other settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>To change the temperature = 温度</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &ldquo;change temperature&rdquo; buttons are usually in the shape of an up and down arrow or have a plus or minus sign on them. In kanji, they are labeled 温度 (&ldquo;<em>ondo</em>,&rdquo; meaning &ldquo;temperature&rdquo;). Press the up arrow or plus sign to raise the temperature. Press the down arrow or minus sign to lower the temperature.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>To change the type of operation = 運転切換</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On my remote control, the type of operation (auto-run, heating, cooling, etc.) is displayed on the screen. When you press the 運転切換 button (&ldquo;<em>unten kirikae</em>,&rdquo; meaning &ldquo;change operation&rdquo;), the little arrow on the screen will go down and point to a different operation. Many Leopalace remote controls are also like this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes, buttons themselves on the remote control will be labeled with the name of the type of operation. In this case, you would press the button labeled with the operation you desired.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following are standard operations included on many Japanese air-conditioners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Types of operations for Japanese air-conditioners</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>自動</strong>&nbsp;(auto-run, &ldquo;<em>jidou</em>&ldquo;)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>冷房</strong>&nbsp;(cooling, &ldquo;<em>reibou</em>&ldquo;)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>除湿</strong>&nbsp;(de-humidifier, &ldquo;<em>joshitsu</em>&ldquo;)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>送風</strong>&nbsp;(ventilator that dries inside of a/c to prevent mold, &ldquo;<em>soufu</em>&ldquo;)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>暖房</strong>&nbsp;(heater, &ldquo;<em>danbou</em>&ldquo;)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>省エネ</strong>&nbsp;(low power-usage, &ldquo;<em>shou ene</em>&ldquo;)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>While many Japanese A/C remote controls have additional buttons, these are the most basic and most used. Hopefully, this Japanese air-conditioner guide can help you create a cool space of your own this summer. Good luck out there.</p>', 'How-to-Use-a-Japanese-Air-Conditioner6.jpg', '2019-05-23 00:00:00', b'1', 4, b'1');
INSERT INTO `blog` (`id_blog`, `title`, `sub_title`, `author`, `category`, `keyword`, `content`, `thumbnail`, `date`, `status`, `read_count`, `like_count`) VALUES
(30, 'The Mask Behind the Mask Culture in Japan', 'Japan\'s love affair with wearing the germ mask gives this author mixed feelings.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Culture', NULL, '<p>For the last two years, I&rsquo;ve visited my nearby Family Mart to pick up bottled water and my other convenience store needs. I often pay the same worker, but I&rsquo;ve never seen his face &mdash; only his eyes and forehead.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor the last year, I&rsquo;ve taught at a university in Tokyo. In that time, I&rsquo;ve had several students who wore white masks every single day of class. Never once did they remove it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA lot <span style=\"color:#ff0000\">has been written</span> <span style=\"color:#ff0000\">regarding mask use in Japan</span>, but it was when I heard that a few employers were beginning to require their workers to wear the mask that I started to feel this should be addressed. The straw that broke the camel&rsquo;s back for me, however, was when I started seeing different colors and designs. Seeing these face coverings &mdash; and what seems to be an over-saturation of their use &mdash; upset me at first. Simply because &mdash; while we all have our own existential love-hate relationship with the human race &mdash; I still want to like people and when interacting with someone, seeing their entire face helps me measure how they feel about me, and, well, how they feel about themselves, too.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://gaijinpot.scdn3.secure.raxcdn.com/app/uploads/sites/4/2015/02/lisa-mask-1024x691.jpg\" style=\"height:691px; width:1024px\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few responses I collected from friends, colleagues, students and even a couple of strangers that I canvassed who have chosen to wear a mask in their daily life. Their answers are paraphrased:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;It keeps me from getting sick on the train since everyone is so close to each other.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;Right now, I&rsquo;m sick so I don&rsquo;t want to give others my sickness.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;Winter is cold and if I wear a mask, I feel warmer.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;My mask is designed to help me not get hay fever.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m trying to protect my privacy. There are cameras everywhere.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to have to feel like I must smile or emote in some way.&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to feel like I need to talk to people.&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>While&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/11/21/reference/face-masks/#.XMAtTegzbIU\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">several popular articles out there</a>&nbsp;have said that modern Japanese society started wearing &ldquo;surgical masks&rdquo; in the early 2000s, the truth is that the &ldquo;germ mask&rdquo; has been used in Japan far longer than that &mdash; try at least 85 years.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&hellip; the &ldquo;germ mask&rdquo; has been used in Japan far longer than that &mdash; try at least 85 years.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is a paragraph from a contributing writer for The Miami News who visited Japan in 1934 and wrote about her experience. Note that this is taken verbatim (and that the now derogatory &ldquo;Jap&rdquo; she uses pre-dates World War II):<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;The Japs have a sense of humor; I read the following in one of their papers: &lsquo;If the inventor of the Japanese germ mask would only get a brain wave and discover a crooner-proof ear muff &mdash; Japanese trade balance with the U.S. would most certainly take on a rosier hue.&rsquo;&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n1934 was also when a flu epidemic spanned the globe, but not to the same extent as the Spanish flu in the late 1910s, which killed millions, and nearly 400,000 people in Japan alone. That a writer for a Japanese newspaper felt comfortable making a joke about a &ldquo;germ mask&rdquo; means that the term was at least in the public consciousness.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYet, since that 1934 remark, the use of the mask in Japan has certainly evolved into an item of protection &mdash; in every sense of the word.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGoing back to the two examples I mentioned at the top: I can see the outside pressures the convenience store worker faces. First, if he were sans mask, he may believe he can be easily detected around the city by other local residents and cameras. In short, his day-to-day life could be tracked &mdash; perhaps even more of a concern for a college-aged female working a part-time job &mdash; so the mask ensures guaranteed anonymity. Employers who require masks probably justify their actions based on sanitary purposes. Perhaps an employee is sick or the product they sell requires a hyper germ-free environment. But the bottom line could very well be that certain people simply don&rsquo;t want to be recognized. This act of social surrender, or purposeful disenfranchisement, saddens me since &mdash; at least to me &mdash; it seems to reflect a lack of self-esteem or an unwillingness to embrace the unpredictability of a chance encounter.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&hellip; the bottom line could very well be that certain people simply don&rsquo;t want to be recognized.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>As for the students I teach, the reason for their masks wasn&rsquo;t because of academic performance. Both scored well. Instead &mdash; and as they expressed to me &mdash; there is an inherent social anxiety that exists within a classroom. A mask excuses them from having to interact with other students or feeling the expectation to be surprised or happy, even when they don&rsquo;t care. In this way, the mask helps double their focus on studies, blocking out interruptions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Learning all this, my mind pictured an Orwellian future with a masked teacher telling a masked class a story about a masked figure saving the lives of masked civilians. Our current definition of identity is quickly flickering out of existence. Perhaps even dating will incorporate the idea of wearing a mask, and only on the third or fourth date will a couple reveal their &ldquo;whole self&rdquo; as they each pull away their multi-colored Sanrio mask. Or, perhaps more realistically, transit authorities will soon require everyone to wear masks on trains and buses to prevent a sickness that has yet to arrive but&nbsp;<em>could</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m not an old man &mdash; early middle-aged, I&rsquo;ll &ldquo;maskingly&rdquo; tell you &mdash; but seeing the growing general popularity of masks irks me. Even when talking with other Westerners, it appears I&rsquo;m somewhat alone in this feeling. I&rsquo;ve seen many non-Japanese wearing a white mask, while others have said that they actually like the custom, as in it offers warmth: they don&rsquo;t feel pressure to have to be&nbsp;<em>genki</em>&nbsp;(full of spirit) all the time. The people can be more careful compared to the &ldquo;careless&rdquo; country from which they come.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All fine, but especially to those who have been willingly wearing a &ldquo;germ mask&rdquo; for months on end, I offer the following quote (admittedly taken out of context). Nathanial Hawthorne, in his novel&nbsp;<em>The Scarlet Letter</em>, once wrote: &ldquo;No man, for any considerable period, can wear one face to himself and another to the multitude, without finally getting bewildered as to which may be true.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I worry about this great country and its devotion to compliance. Couldn&rsquo;t the mask sink the nation&rsquo;s residents into a deeper form of passivity? Does it not in some way symbolize the loss of one&rsquo;s voice &mdash; an inverted silent protest or an erasure of personality?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maybe I&rsquo;m taking it all too seriously. After all, it takes just as much free will to put a mask on as it does to take one off. &nbsp;But whenever I&rsquo;m having a conversation with a permanent mask wearer &mdash; or PMW &mdash; I can&rsquo;t help but feel confused: Do you&nbsp;<em>want</em>&nbsp;to talk to me? And, if the masked discussion goes on for longer than a minute: How do you&nbsp;<em>feel</em>&nbsp;about what I&rsquo;m saying &mdash; because your eyes are only part of your story.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Do you wear surgical masks in Japan to protect yourself from colds and allergies? Do you wear one for other reasons? Let us know in the comments!</em></p>', 'masks-01-1024x768.jpg', '2019-05-23 00:00:00', b'1', 3, b'1'),
(31, '10 things have to be prepared before live in Japan', 'Living abroad is one of the exciting moment in some people who love challenges, but sometimes a new territory will be quite a handful of things if you don’t prepare enough.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nHere are our 10 tips what are things to be prepared to live in Japan.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Living abroad is one of the exciting moment in some people who love challenges, but sometimes a new territory will be quite a handful of things if you don&rsquo;t prepare enough.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Here are our 10 tips what are things to be prepared to live in Japan.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>1. Visa</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Visa comes with many different of types, but if you plan to work in Japan don&rsquo;t forget to apply the Work Visa and carefully count your living plan in Japan, and don&rsquo;t forget to ask your company to attach letter of recommendation for you.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>2. Cash for 1 - 3 month</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Make sure that you always have enough on you. For many things, Japan is still a cash society and sometimes you will hear &ldquo;crejitto ca-do tsukaemasen&rdquo; (no credit cards.), and you want to refuel your cash, you can go to the convenient store and draw your money on ATM.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>3. Get Suica/ Pasmo </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>These are rechargeable cash cards that you swipe in and out of the station saving you the hassle of buying tickets each time. Get them at any station and don&rsquo;t be afraid when going through the ticket barrier if you see a whole crowd coming towards you &ndash; they work from both ends. Plus, you can use those at convenience stores and vending machines.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>4. &nbsp;Apply for your health insurance right away</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Once you have registered your address in your local ward office, if you aren&rsquo;t employed full time here (or aren&rsquo;t using your spouse&rsquo;s insurance) you will be set up with national health insurance coverage which requires monthly payments. The insurance covers 70 percent of your medical costs and you will be required to pay the remaining 30. If you need to bring medication into Japan you&rsquo;ll need proof from your doctor on arrival &ndash; ask your embassy about the requirements before you leave. &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>5. &nbsp;Temporary living place</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>For working in Japan, usually company will cover you for a temporary living place. But if you stay as full time worker you will cover you own living expenses. You can ask your company to assist you to find a suitable temporary living place. or simply go to our article &ldquo; How to rent an apartment as foreigner in Japan &ldquo;.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>6. Medicine </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Japan has its own brand and also has different doses when it comes with the medicine. So it is better that you could bring your own health package with you.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>7. &nbsp;Bring your favorite pre-processed food with you</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Sometimes food can be a major problem for someone, so it is a good idea to bring your favorite food with you, but do not forget to check the expired date of each food so you can count on your ransom, but if you already familiar with local food, search on the internet what to eat for everyday&rsquo;s menu on the internet. But japan right now has different types of food that can be consume to global and also they has Muslim friendly food that you can bought daily, you can also download the apps on your mobile for halal food guidance.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>8. Bring your Winter coat and Summer set clothes</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Winter in Japan can be lethal for some people, especially for they live in the south east asia region, and the heat on Summer will be your enemy during the day. So, don&rsquo;t forget to bring your Winter and Summer set clothes, or also you can buy them at Japan and price is quite affordable, if you don&rsquo;t want to bust your cash to pay your extra baggage.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>9. Internet access</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Japan has internet services can be easily accessible for any foreigner, but if you plan to living there you can go to electronic store such Bic Camera, and plan your monthly internet access package, you can choose the internet with or without the device ( smartphone ),</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>10. Plan your day to day schedule</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Japan has a tight schedule in every way, so make sure you plan your schedule tight enough to adapt your daily activity to make a better output so you can live adaptly and enjoyable. and don&rsquo;t forget to download free apps on your phone to help you adjust your schedule daily.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(1).jpg', '2019-05-23 13:43:01', b'1', 6, b'1'),
(41, 'HUAWEI BATAL RILIS DI JEPANG', 'HP kesayanganmu baru saja di banned oleh Amerika, dan kini Jepang berikutnya. Hm, ada apa sebenarnya?', 'GeeksJapan', 'Uncategorized', NULL, '<p>KDDI dan Softbank, dan bahkan sang no.1 DoCoMo (nama provider telekomunikasi terkemuka di Jepang), juga berencana untuk membatalkan perilisan mobile phone baru keluaran Huawei di Jepang. Terkait dengan larangan yang dikeluarkan oleh Trump di Amerika, bersama dengan Google. Pasalnya dugaan masalah kebocoran sekuritas, dan penyalahgunaan pemakaian kekayaan intelektual, yang pastinya terus disangkal oleh perusahaan pembuat smartphone no.2 di dunia ini. Hm, jadi penasaran...apa kabar smartphone Sony ya?</p>', 'huawei2.png', '2019-05-23 14:08:01', b'1', 8, b'1'),
(42, 'Living cost in Japan', 'We will try to breakdown the living cost based on the general information on the big city in Japan ( because the living cost depends on the place that you are living in Japan)', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Work in Japan is somehow become everyone&rsquo;s dream who is in love with the Pop culture, Technology, and even the scenery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, have you already know about how much is the living cost in Japan?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We will try to breakdown the living cost based on the general information on the big city in Japan ( because the living cost depends on the place that you are living in Japan)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Apartemen ( 6x6 M2 )</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">50,000 Yen - 75,0000 Yen ( 455 USD - 682 USD )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Electric bill ( depends on the electronic devices you use, this price a general price on average usage based on smartphone, laptop )</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">4,000 Yen - 7,000 Yen ( 36 USD - 64 USD )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Water Bill ( general usage price )</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">3,000 Yen - 6,000 Yen ( 27 USD - 55 USD )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Gas Bill ( General usage price )</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">3,000 Yen - 6,000 Yen &nbsp;( 27 USD - 55 USD )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Daily Meal</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">500 Yen - 1000 Yen / meal ( 5 USD - 10 USD )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Train Card</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">10,000 Yen / Month ( General usage )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Internet/ Wifi ( General Usage )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Full package Internet, Wifi, and Smartphone</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">10,000 Yen/ Month ( General Usage )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Smartphone and Internet</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">6,000 Yen - 10,000 Yen ( General usage )</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Total per month ( Yen )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Apartemen 75,000</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Electrical Bill 7,000</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Water Bill 6,000</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Gas Bill 6,000</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Meal ( 30 days) 30,000 (1000 x 30 )</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Train Card 10,000</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Internet+Smartphone 10,000</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">_________________ +</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">154,000 Yen / Month</p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan.jpg', '2019-05-27 09:22:22', b'1', 8, b'1'),
(43, 'Mobile apps can that can be helpful in Japan', 'Living in the country with a different language is one of the challenges we should face, other than how the local peoples speak, but also facing a different character of alphabet structure is somehow frustrating for the monolinguals.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Living in the country with a different language is one of the challenges we should face, other than how the local peoples speak, but also facing a different character of alphabet structure is somehow frustrating for the monolinguals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But Apps these day makes everything easier for us</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">1. Google Translate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">No wonder these apps would come useful whenever you go, the google translate also featured an Augmented Reality with a live translation. so whenever you directed your camera with the apps the translation will appear directly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2. NaviTime</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This app will help you everywhere in Japan to catch on your train schedule, bus, and which line, best price, and also guide you to find the route to your destination.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">3. Line</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Chat platform for any purposes, this is the biggest platform you will find in Japan. and sometimes can offer you a great deal for your favorite items or brands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">4. &nbsp;Food finder apps</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This app&nbsp;depends on what kind of food that you want to eat, for Halal food specification you can download Halal gourmet, and for general Japanese food guide you can download Guru Navi, both are available on IOS and Android.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">5. Google Maps</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Basically, this app will guide you to places where you want to go.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">6. Hotel Booking apps</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This app&nbsp;allows you to find a temporary stay while in Japan, you can download apps such as Airbnb, Tripadvisor, Booking.com, and many more</p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(2).jpg', '2019-05-27 09:49:51', b'1', 8, b'1'),
(44, 'How to survive Winter in Japan', 'Whether it is your first winter in Japan or you are a seasoned veteran, you have no doubt realized that Japanese homes are not designed to hold back the cold from creeping into your room. But do not fret dear reader, for we have you covered with the top ten ways to keep you from setting fire to the tatami to keep warm.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p>Whether it is your first winter in Japan or you are a seasoned veteran, you have no doubt realized that Japanese homes are not designed to hold back the cold from creeping into your room. But do not fret dear reader, for we have you covered with the top ten ways to keep you from setting fire to the tatami to keep warm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>10. Double up with thick curtains and seal your windows</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The biggest drafts will come in through your paper thin, single pane glass windows. One of the cheapest ways to insulate the windows is with rolls of bubble wrap that can be purchased for only a few hundred yen per role at most 100 yen stores.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>9. Invest in a good pair of socks and slippers</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This combo will help make the morning walk out of bed a bit less painful when your look at the cold, pseudo-wood panel flooring. If you really want to go the extra mile, have a back up set for any guests that come through. Remember to keep a separate pair for use in the bathroom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>8. Invite friends over for nabe (hot-pot) dinner</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, you may have to sacrifice a few yen to keep your heater running so your guests don&rsquo;t freeze, but the added body heat and hot-pot of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blog.gaijinpot.com/japanese-nabe/\">food and drink</a>&nbsp;will make for a perfect cozy evening.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>7. Bring out the kotatsu (Japanese heated table)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have not discovered this magical winter den yet, you may not survive the cold long enough to get the end of this list. The kotatsu (炬燵) is a table that has a small heater built under it. Put a heavy quilt between the two top tables, turn the heater on and slide your lower body under for some nice electric toastiness! This device is also a favourite of cats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>6. Layout the electric carpet</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although many of the older versions were electricity hungry and would eat up your utility bill, modern electric blankets can heat up your cold posterior for a few yen an hour. The most efficient method to use one is to place it on top of your couch and use a blanket to trap in all of the warmth. Make sure to have a sufficient supply of foodstuffs nearby so that you never have to get up, ever.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>5. Take a long soak in the bath</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Japan is the land of baths and most bathtubs in apartments come with high tech versions that automatically fill and constantly reheat the water. There is nothing better than relaxing after a cold day while heating your body to the core. If you do not have a bath that is large enouigh, find the nearest onsen or sento and get to know your neighbours in a new and intimate way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>4. Invest in an electric kettle</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is nothing more satisfying than an everlasting supply of hot water to fuel you with your choice winter beverage. If you are ready to drop a bit of cash, you may want to get a traditional electric kettle that continuously heats water as it cools. If you are hoping for a quick and cheap solution without setting a pot on a stove, finding a low spec electric kettle should do the trick and give you just the amount of hot water you need.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3. Hang out at the local mall</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a reason that old people are known to power-walk in air conditioned complexes, it&rsquo;s because they are smart. Braving the trip to the nearest AEON on super mall will be well worth the journey. Drink up the free coffee samples at the international goods store, give the granny giving out free nabe samples a wink, and make sure everyone is having just as great of a day as you are.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2. Stock up on adhesive hot packs/pocket warmers</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In most countries, hot packs are mostly used to fill your pockets when you are enjoying snow sports. But like most great things, Japan has taken this product to the next level by making a variety of warmers from shoe-inlays to aroma therapy versions. The best of these are the versions with the removable adhesive backing that you can stick anywhere you like. Although they easily last for 24 hours at about 30 JPY a sheet, put a little thought into where you stick them and never apply one directly to your skin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1. Get out of the country</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you can manage to plan ahead for the winter, save up enough holiday and cash to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blog.gaijinpot.com/not-in-japan-anymore/\">fly yourself to a warmer climate</a>. Naturally, nothing is better than a warm cup of hot cocoa on your parents&rsquo; couch, but if that is not an option look to closer shores. There are plenty of warmer places where you won&rsquo;t have to be reminded why you left home to begin with only a short flight away. Guam, Okinawa, and Thailand are not as far away as you might think!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Source link article :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://blog.gaijinpot.com/10-tips-surviving-winter-japan/\">https://blog.gaijinpot.com/10-tips-surviving-winter-japan/</a><br />\r\nPhoto sources:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.newsweek.com/snow-monkeys-bathe-hot-springs-relieve-stress-humans-study-macaque-japan-872817\">https://www.newsweek.com/snow-monkeys-bathe-hot-springs-relieve-stress-humans-study-macaque-japan-872817</a></p>', 'Satori-Reader-Lead@0_5x-1.png', '2019-05-27 10:04:21', b'1', 9, b'1'),
(45, '5 Secret Ways to Survive Summer the Japanese Way', '5 Secret Ways to Survive Summer the Japanese Way\r\n\r\nBasically this is how to become native and spend your time like a local.\r\n\r\nHow to spend your free time on summer vacation in Japan', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p>1.Kaki gori (かき氷) shaved ice</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Compared with their western counterpart, the Japanese ice called Kakigōri (かき氷) is a much more healthier kind of ice, flavoured with syrup and a sweetener. Since the base is plain shaved ice, it has far less calories than milk based ice. Standard flavours include strawberry, cherry, lemon, green tea, grape, melon, and Blue Hawaii. It is often sold at convenience stores and a must have at summer festivals, the so called o-matsuri (お祭り).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.Suika (スイカ) Watermelon</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Summer is the season of watermelons in Japan. Be warned, they are a bit pricey, but essential, and the Japanese immediately associate watermelon with summer. It is also a popular game on the beach to try to crack a watermelon blindfolded, which is then shared and eaten together.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.Kaidan (怪談) Ghost stories</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A rather unique approach on fighting summer heat is to read or tell each other ghost stories. If they are good, you will get goose bumps and can cool down a bit during boiling days, or evenings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.Sensu (扇子) Japanese fan</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Foldable fans are more convenient in daily life, but the bigger round types, which are nowadays usually made of plastic have a stronger effect. The latter ones are often distributed near stations with an advertisement on it, so if you happen to forget your own, you can count on getting one near a major station.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.Furin (風鈴) Windchime</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How can a wind bell cool you down? The idea is simple: when the wind is blowing, the breeze is playing the chime, which then &ldquo;announces&rdquo; to the listener, that hopefully a cool wind is blowing. Japanese then imagine the cool breeze and enjoy the feeling, even if not experiencing it first hand. The visual and aural garden ornament is usually played by the wind frequently during the day and is the perfect mental cooler!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Article source :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://jpninfo.com/11177\">https://jpninfo.com/11177</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Photo source :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-mRCgaxKBqHI/Wn_fnF3tPZI/AAAAAAABYh4/Yx_zMj_QvFsY9fERZzgRFe4QP3uVzrAkQCLcBGAs/s1600/01%2BJPN_7942%2BToyako%2BOnsen%2BSummer%2BFestival%2Bin%2B2017%2B%2540%2BLake%2BToya%2B%255BHokkaido%252C%2BJapan%255D.JPG\">https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-mRCgaxKBqHI/Wn_fnF3tPZI/AAAAAAABYh4/Yx_zMj_QvFsY9fERZzgRFe4QP3uVzrAkQCLcBGAs/s1600/01%2BJPN_7942%2BToyako%2BOnsen%2BSummer%2BFestival%2Bin%2B2017%2B%2540%2BLake%2BToya%2B%255BHokkaido%252C%2BJapan%255D.JPG</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(4).jpg', '2019-05-27 10:14:45', b'1', 23, b'1'),
(52, 'Affordable food you can buy in Japan', 'Minimarket might not be the place that comes to your mind when we’re talking about a place to eat. However when you’re looking for a place which you can find affordable food, you can’t skip minimarket as it has a wide variety of low price yet delicious food. Minimarket or konbini in Japanese can be found in almost every corner of Japan, especially in the big city, which means anytime you feel hungry, you can easily find a minimarket to stop by and buy some food. Another good thing is they usually have tables and chairs for those who want to eat their food on the spot.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">Minimarket might not be the place that comes to your mind when we&rsquo;re talking about a place to eat. However when you&rsquo;re looking for a place which you can find affordable food, you can&rsquo;t skip minimarket as it has a wide variety of low price yet delicious food. Minimarket or konbini in Japanese can be found in almost every corner of Japan, especially in the big city, which means anytime you feel hungry, you can easily find a minimarket to stop by and buy some food. Another good thing is they usually have tables and chairs for those who want to eat their food on the spot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So here we go with the affordable food list you can find in Japanese minimarket:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Instant ramen</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Instant ramen is considered as one of the most favourite food choice as it&rsquo;s usually cheap in terms of price (you can find many instant ramen which price is lower than 500 yen!) and easy to make. In Japan, it&rsquo;s not uncommon to buy a ramen (noodles) in minimarket and then eat it right away because they provide free hot water for making instant ramen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Frozen food</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are many varieties of frozen food to choose, from pasta to Japanese meal. The frozen food is usually packed in a single portion and have different prices according to the variety. However you can still find some with price lower than 500 yen. The good news is, Japanese minimarket also provide microwave to heat this type of food with no additional charge so you can eat it warm. All you need to do is to ask the store attendant to warm the food in the microwave when you purchase it. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Bread</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As a country that&rsquo;s known to eat rice as its main menu, bread is surprisingly very popular too. Not to mention that Japan has many unique bread flavours which might never be found &nbsp;anywhere else such as yakisoba pan (hotdog like bread with fried noodles as its filling) and melon pan (round shaped bun with crusty cookie like crust). Now, if you&rsquo;re looking for the affordable one, you can buy the specially packed small breads (usually around 4-6 breads in a pack). This way, not only you&rsquo;ll get more bread to fill in your stomach, this pack also has a pretty affordable price considering the amount of bread inside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Bento</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Whoever visits Japan will get used to see the infamous single portion take-out Japanese meal, bento. In a set of meal there&rsquo;s already rice, vegetable and the side dish (mostly seafood, chicken, beef or pork). Some places promote bento as a special set meal, no wonder why its price is pretty high. However if you want to have a taste of it, you can try your luck by looking for the affordable one in the minimarket. Though it&rsquo;d a bit more pricey than the other foods mentioned before, you can still get the &ldquo;around 500 yen&rdquo; bento.</p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(5).jpg', '2019-05-31 10:54:11', b'1', 2, b'1'),
(53, 'A basic guide to Japanese toilet seat', 'One of the unique thing that impressed many visitors in Japan is the “super fancy” toilet seat that seems like an item from the future at the first glance. Unlike the other “simple” toilet seat around the world, Japanese toilet seat is very modern and has many buttons which highkey may cause confusion for those who had just seen it for the first time (especially those who can’t read kanji). These set of buttons mostly have basic functions just like the ordinary ones, therefore once you get the gist of it, it’d be very convenient for you to use it.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>One of the unique thing that impressed many visitors in Japan is the &ldquo;super fancy&rdquo; toilet seat that seems like an item from the future at the first glance. Unlike the other &ldquo;simple&rdquo; toilet seat around the world, Japanese toilet seat is very modern and has many buttons which highkey may cause confusion for those who had just seen it for the first time (especially those who can&rsquo;t read kanji). These set of buttons mostly have basic functions just like the ordinary ones, therefore once you get the gist of it, it&rsquo;d be very convenient for you to use it. </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Although it&rsquo;s not rare to find the buttons with an image on each of them to give a brief explanation of its function or even english words written, there are also those who barely have any of them (only kanji). So here we provide you the basic guide to use the high tech Japanese toilet seat.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>First let&rsquo;s start with the flush as it&rsquo;s one of the most basic function in the toilet. Generally the flush button &nbsp;(written as 流す or ながす in Japanese) isn&rsquo;t included in the control panel but some cases beg to differ. Some toilet have the manual handle or button for flush, some have the sensoric press button on the wall (pict.1) while the others have the automatic flush function that uses sensor to detect. In some cases you can also choose the intensity of the flush water : big (大) or small (小).</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/Om9q5pDO83LOECSl2coP3nSp9vfBmdRiJNYf3ZtQ87-3baSjvqa6dXdsRnrC-vjGKsiaPISwXJ5EQqgYTq4ovbyo8bCjnnXzBkigwcs0w4GOQo8Tcv-wB7nukNWik9TbspLrLWvr\" style=\"height:238px; width:471px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Basically there are two types of toilet control panel, the first type is attached to the toilet seat (pict.3) while the other is attached to the wall (pict.2). From these pictures (pict.2 and 3), you could also see the sink on top of the toilet to wash your hand. This type of sink often has the automatic sensor so you don&rsquo;t have to press any buttons nor handle.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/Vmt7O6qGS4dh-dprETuqqhTLXCw8eJANP_PhnG-pBM_5dIigd54M8vZOAvEbk0i190-iPXayFRy6BXAR1o_0J1Sckh9siRhXEwf0ajSMx6HFPOal1EfuSBfbRLJvQZYlXgPK4cQD\" style=\"height:234px; width:350px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>There are two basic buttons for washing (pict.4): front washing (bidet : ビデ) and rear washing (oshiri: おしり &nbsp;or yawaraka: やわらか for softer spray). In many control panels, they also provide you with water pressure (水勢) or water temperature (温水) buttons to suit your preference. Usually the adjustment options available for these choices are high (高), medium (中) and low (低), strong (強) and weak (弱), or just simply &ldquo;+&rdquo; and &ldquo;-&ldquo;.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/wn4mM6McYnodF7lvgkc54gm9zBrvrsUzWiRARD7Fyy5keJXq_izhvqAG-0HW8x8mxW6qFwwrROR_gTPLwtMFdoYpIIATLKDPFlBkR-ijYhX78NkfYpbLhUsfTIL4LzXEXIsxurN3\" style=\"height:113px; width:360px\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Lastly, one of the most basic buttons is &ldquo;stop (止)&rdquo;. The function is to stop any present activated features. Most of the time you&rsquo;ll see this button has orange colour and appears in bigger size than the rest of the buttons on the control panel.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Aside from the basic functions in the previous explanation, there&rsquo;re also some optional functions such as:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Air dryer (乾燥) : just as the name stated, its function is to dry yourself after washing. For this function, some has the cool or warm options too.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Power deodorizer (パワー脱臭) : it will spray some scent to get rid of the unwanted smell</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Toilet seat warmer (便座) : this is especially helpful during winter time when the cold air has a very big possibility to make the toilet seat as cold as ice. </strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Sound (音量) : probably this is the most interesting feature as we might only find it in Japan. This feature will play a sound that resembles the running water or flushing sound to cover up the &ldquo;displeasing&rdquo; sound. Some toilet has this feature automatically activate using a sensor to detect the user presence. If this is the case then you don&rsquo;t have to worry because it&rsquo;ll turn off on its own.</strong></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Source: </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><a href=\"https://thetruejapan.com/how-to-use-a-japanese-high-tech-toilet/\">https://thetruejapan.com/how-to-use-a-japanese-high-tech-toilet/</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><a href=\"http://www.survivingnjapan.com/2013/07/how-to-use-electronic-japanese-toilet.html\">http://www.survivingnjapan.com/2013/07/how-to-use-electronic-japanese-toilet.html</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong><a href=\"https://matcha-jp.com/en/1256\">https://matcha-jp.com/en/1256</a></strong></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(7).jpg', '2019-05-31 12:52:18', b'1', 4, b'1'),
(54, 'Muslim guide: where to pray in Japan', 'As as a Muslim, one of the challenging thing to face while staying in Japan might be to find a place to pray. However in these recent years, considering the potential of Muslim visitors, Japan started to put more attention in this case like providing halal certificates for many products and restaurants as well as praying rooms in strategic public places.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">As as a Muslim, one of the challenging thing to face while staying in Japan might be to find a place to pray. However in these recent years, considering the potential of Muslim visitors, Japan started to put more attention in this case like providing halal certificates for many products and restaurants as well as praying rooms in strategic public places.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here we have summarize in a list of places for praying in Japan including the potential ones in case you don&rsquo;t find any decent places for praying nearby :</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Mosque</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The first mosque built in Japan in 1935 is located in Kobe, since then though there aren&rsquo;t that many, more mosques came to exist throughout Japan. Some of them are located in well known areas like Tokyo, Osaka, Kyoto and Hokkaido, but there are also those that located in other regions like Kanagawa, Aichi &nbsp;and Ehime For more details you can check the list of mosque here: <a href=\"https://muslim-guide.jp/mosque/\">https://muslim-guide.jp/mosque/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Praying Room</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nowadays Japan are providing more praying rooms in strategic places like train stations, airports as well as several touristic places including shopping malls. You need to take a note that some places might need a reservation to use the praying rooms so make sure to check the requirement first. Just for your information, these praying rooms are usually very comfortable since Japan takes a good care of them. For now we&rsquo;re gonna spill some places that provide prayer rooms : Tokyo Narita and Haneda Airport, Kansai Ariport (Osaka), Fukuoka Airport, New Chitose Airport (Hokkaido), Naha Airport (Okinawa), Tokyo Station, Osaka Station City, Aeon (only in 5 stores), Laox (several stores too), and many more. Or if you want more info, just go to this link to find around 287 praying spaces throughout Japan: <a href=\"https://masjid-finder.jp/pray?utf8=%E2%9C%93&amp;q%5Bprefecture_id_eq%5D=&amp;q%5Bpray_category_id_eq%5D=&amp;button=\">https://masjid-finder.jp/pray?utf8=%E2%9C%93&amp;q%5Bprefecture_id_eq%5D=&amp;q%5Bpray_category_id_eq%5D=&amp;button=</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">First Aid Room</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you happen to be in touristic places like theme park for example that has no praying rooms at all, you might try your luck by going to first aid room. Since it&rsquo;s common to have first aid room in such places but usually there aren&rsquo;t many people there, you can try to ask for permission to use one of the booth there for several minutes to pray. The curtain that surrounds the booth in the first aid room is good to give you some privacy, besides there&rsquo;ll be most likely no one that dares to disturb you if you surround yourself with the curtains in the booth. You just have to remember to show your gratefulness by not spending a long time there and making sure everything is tidied up exactly like how you entered it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Maternity Room</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is an option that might work if you&rsquo;re a female. In advanced society like Japan, maternity room can be found in many public areas. Therefore if it&rsquo;s you&rsquo;re in a public area that hardly has any praying rooms nearby, you can take this option. Maternity room usually located near the toilet, so it&rsquo;ll be easy for you to take wudu and go straight to the maternity room for praying. If there&rsquo;s no one that use the maternity room while you&rsquo;re using it, it&rsquo;d feel like a private space since it&rsquo;s not visible from the outside. But since that&rsquo;s not always be the case, you have to count in the possibility of sharing the room with the others. Unfortunately maternity room isn&rsquo;t that spacious, so you better pray in the corner that will less likely get in the way of those who want to use the room too. If there&rsquo;s anyone that use the room before you came, it&rsquo;d be more polite to ask for their permissions. Japanese women are usually very considerate so they&rsquo;ll let you pray, but just in case some of them don&rsquo;t feel comfortable with it, you need to let them know first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Emergency Stairs</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Emergency stairs is like a basic requirements in a country like Japan that&rsquo;s fully aware of the danger from natural disaster that often happens there. It&rsquo;s not a daily use facility though with the existence of elevators so in most cases there won&rsquo;t be anyone that&rsquo;s using it. This is a good thing if you&rsquo;re in dire need to pray but happens to be somewhere far away from any praying rooms nor mosque since there&rsquo;ll be a slim chance of getting disturb by somebody that&rsquo;s passing by. Emergency stairs usually have an entrance / exit door in each floor which is great for it will give you a sense of &ldquo;privacy&rdquo;. If you decide to pray here, please be reminded to do it as quickly as possible because some people use it for smoking place too, and some emergency stairs might be located &ldquo;outside&rdquo; the building so if you&rsquo;re praying here, it&rsquo;ll be somewhat visible from the outside (it won&rsquo;t be comfortable of course).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source :</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://tdjapan.com/%20articles/halal-info-in-japan/japan-airport-prayer-rooms\">https://tdjapan.com/%20articles/halal-info-in-japan/japan-airport-prayer-rooms</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(6).jpg', '2019-06-12 08:29:41', b'1', 3, b'1');
