(55, 'Hottest Job in Japan', 'It’s not easy to decide the indicators for saying which job is the hottest in Japan at the moment. Especially if we’re talking to different audiences : the Japanese and the global. So for now, we let the data talks and view some so-called high demand job for foreigners.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/rMYLuFnIeT7Q5Lf7lvzgyG7rbwe9esCJajFrWMxRJfGW5AhCT5zEiDd9t6XI2upB2mtBnGYCFTMdvxPrFxRTHl6K3yOkD0HukbePfPxrpBRGfEXk1bDieso1Pl7BEdS0y7uurGf0\" style=\"height:338px; width:539px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It&rsquo;s not easy to decide the indicators for saying which job is the hottest in Japan at the moment. Especially if we&rsquo;re talking to different audiences: the Japanese and the global. So for now, we let the data talks and view some so-called high demand job for foreigners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">First let us see the result of an annual salary survey by one of the Japanese job site, DODA (doda.jp), which conducted in 2017. The survey suggest that the average salary in Japan was ￥4,180,000 (around ＄37,192, with the estimation of 1 USD = 112 JPY) with two thirds of top 30 highest paying jobs are related to Information Technology (IT) and business planning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If we see the types of job said to be in high demand within foreigners, IT professional indeed gets in the list. But aside from that, we&rsquo;ve also narrowed down some jobs that might be in line with your interest:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">IT Professional</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Not only it&rsquo;s considered to have a high salary, this job is on high demand since technology plays a big part in an advanced country like Japan. It professionals like software engineers and programmers are being hire by many Japanese companies and it&rsquo;s not showing any signs of decreasing. In this job, generally your Japanese ability isn&rsquo;t that required so it&rsquo;s pretty convenient for those who aren&rsquo;t a quick learner of Japanese.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Engineer</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Known for its advanced engineering, it&rsquo;s only logical that many Japanese companies are open to hire foreign engineers. From electronics, automotive to heavy industries,. Japan sure has many engineering jobs in store for those who crave it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Banker</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Probably just like anywhere else, banker is a common job that&rsquo;s always been a popular choice within the society. Though it isn&rsquo;t a stable environment, some large investment banks have a record of hiring foreign staff to be relocated in Japan. The banking industry itself supports job in IT sector and pays a great deal. Some even say that the salary for IT staff in investment bank industry is far more higher than the one in manufacturing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">English Teacher</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the past this might be the best job for foreigners in Japan since the salary was excellent. Unfortunately, that&rsquo;s not how it works nowadays. Even so, it&rsquo;s still a popular job for foreigners since an English teacher job is always on high demand in Japan and the fact that it doesn&rsquo;t require a proper teaching credentials (unless if it&rsquo;s the Japanese government&rsquo;s JET program) makes the opportunity to join in seems bigger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Service Staff</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are only two basic requirements for working in this job : valid visa and good Japanese language skills. Considering how Japan try their best in expanding the tourism industry, the service staff with bilingual ability is seen as a promising trait. There is no doubt that hotels, resorts, restaurants and cafes in popular tourist area are seeking for individuals with bilingual ability to serve their customers. Now, if you posses those two requirements, why not try and give it a go?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://resources.realestate.co.jp/living/what-are-the-best-paying-jobs-and-industries-in-japan-2018-survey/\">https://resources.realestate.co.jp/living/what-are-the-best-paying-jobs-and-industries-in-japan-2018-survey/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/the-8-most-popular-jobs-for-foreigners-in-japan/\">https://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/the-8-most-popular-jobs-for-foreigners-in-japan/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(8).jpg', '2019-06-12 08:51:21', b'1', 5, b'1'),
(56, 'What is Working Hours in Japan?', 'We might’ve heard in the news about Japanese people who’s very diligent with their work that he’s even willing to work overtime over and over again for it. Putting aside the tendency of being loyal dan discipline in Japanese themselves,  do you ever wonder how long is the actual working hours in Japan? And what makes these people have to go with working over time countlessly?', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">We might&rsquo;ve heard in the news about Japanese people who&rsquo;s very diligent with their work that he&rsquo;s even willing to work overtime over and over again for it. Putting aside the tendency of being loyal dan discipline in Japanese themselves, &nbsp;do you ever wonder how long is the actual working hours in Japan? And what makes these people have to go with working over time countlessly?</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Let&rsquo;s start this by explaining the Japanese working hours system. Basically we can divide the main types of working hours in Japan into three categories:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Fixed time system (固定時間制度, kotei jikan seido)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is the most common type of working hours being used in Japan. In this system there&rsquo;s a fixed schedule: from 8 am - 5 pm or 9 am - 6 pm per day including one hour break time or in short 8 hours per day. In a week, people with this type of system will work from Monday to Friday, so in total they&rsquo;ll have to work for 40 hours per week. The &ldquo;8 hours a day, 40 hours a week&rdquo; are called &ldquo;statutory working hours&rdquo;. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Flexible time system (フレックスタイム制度, furekkusu taimu seido)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This type mostly adopted by designers, design works and IT companies. In this system the person gets to choose freely their start and end time as long as it&rsquo;s still within the range of the agreed working hours and still keep the average time based on the statutory working hours (8 hours a day, 40 hours a week). However, depending on each company&rsquo;s policy, they might as well set a core time in which all employees have to be present in order to secure time to work jointly, run a meetings, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Discretionary labor system (裁量労働制度, sairyō rōdō seido)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This type of system oversees the actual working hours because what&rsquo;s seen is whether or not the amount of work given done.In a way this is good because a person can decide personally on how and when to work without being tied by a specific time nor schedule. But the downside of this system is that though it oversees the time, the work must be finished as promised, therefore regardless of the actual amount of time a person has spent, even if he / she works on the weekends or holidays, it&rsquo;s still counted the same. In the worst scenario, such system might lead to excessive overtime working hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the official rules (Section 4. Human Resource Management, 4.5 Legislation on working hours, breaks and day off), there are several points that we can highlight:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Working hours must, in principle, not exceed 40 hours per week or eight hours per day excluding breaks (this is known as &ldquo;statutory working hours&rdquo;). However, some businesses are permitted to have their employees work up to 44 hours per week at a maximum of eight hours per day (4.5.1.1)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Employers must grant employees at least one day off per week, or four days off in any four-week period (this is known as &ldquo;statutory days off&rdquo;). Sundays or public holiday need not necessarily be days off, and other days may be selected as employees&rsquo; days off instead by the agreement between the employer and employees. (4.5.1.3)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Companies must pay an increased rate of wages as set forth in the table below* to employees who work in excess of statutory working hours, work on statutory days off or work late at night (between 22:00 - 05.00) (4.5.4)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If we see the result of various questionnaires on overtime hours, majority of the workers confessed that the overtime hours in a month are more than 30 hours, so in average they&rsquo;re working overtime for about 1- 2 hours a day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With all the information above we can conclude that the working hours in Japan still considered fair whether if we view it from the actual regulations or the real implementations itself. Though cases like excessive overtime hours has a possibility to occur, it&rsquo;s not something that most likely happens that often. As long as we know the rules and the limit, and being aware of our own conditions, there shouldn&rsquo;t be a problem with working in Japan. Instead, there might be many things we could learn from Japanese work ethics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">(*see the actual legislation for details)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.jetro.go.jp/en/invest/setting_up/section4/page5.html\">https://www.jetro.go.jp/en/invest/setting_up/section4/page5.html</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://talenthub.jp/blog/working-in-japan/what-are-working-hours-in-japan/\">https://talenthub.jp/blog/working-in-japan/what-are-working-hours-in-japan/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(9).jpg', '2019-06-14 15:09:01', b'1', 2, b'1'),
(57, 'Experience Unbelievably Cost Free Travel in Tokyo', '“No money? No problem!” is probably the perfect phrase for this case. When you’re short on the budget, these worth trying things to do or places to visit in Tokyo can be real saviours that you can’t even believe it costs you nothing. Who says great memories can only be achieved by spending lots of money?', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;No money? No problem!&rdquo; is probably the perfect phrase for this case. When you&rsquo;re short on the budget, these worth trying things to do or places to visit in Tokyo can be real saviours that you can&rsquo;t even believe it costs you nothing. Who says great memories can only be achieved by spending lots of money?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Public places tourist attractions</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many well known tourist destinations include public places like statues and pedestrian streets.Harajuku, Shibuya, Akihabara and Odaiba for example are actually names of areas where everybody can freely visit. You just need to take note on the iconic places of each area and take photos as the prove. Some of the icons you better put in the list are Hachiko statue, Shibuya crossing, Takeshita dori, Rainbow Bridge, and Gundam statue. Don&rsquo;t forget either that there are many beautiful parks too that are open to the public for free like Ueno Park, Yoyogi Park, and Tokyo Imperial Palace East Garden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Enjoy the scenery with no worry</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Depending on the season, Japan has different sceneries. One of the most favourite scenery is the sakura blossoms in spring, Basically sakura tree can be found in many places across Japan even in streets or housing complex. But many people prefer to gather in public areas like parks to enjoy the beautiful view. This sakura blossoms viewing tradition is called &ldquo;hanami&rdquo;. Of course everyone is free to join in and it&rsquo;s free of charge. Other type of scenery that you can enjoy is the city scape from the skyscraper. While Tokyo Tower or Tokyo Skytree demands you to pay for bucks, you can actually have a free glimpse of the same view from Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building, Carrot Tower, or Bunkyo Civic Center.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Free admission tourist attractions</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some shrines like Meiji Shrine in Harajuku and Sensoji Temple in Asakusa are known for being open to the public without any admission fee, but believe it or not there are also museums, zoo and boat ride that cost you no money too. In Edogawa Ward, there&rsquo;s Edogawa Natural Zoo, a free admission zoo where you can see many adorable animals and even get the chance to pet some of them on the scheduled hours, while in Koto Ward, there&rsquo;s a traditional Japanese wooden boat (wasen) tour along the Yokojikkengawa Canal for about 10 minutes that&rsquo;s offered for free. If you&rsquo;re interested to join the boat tour, just go to the Koto ward office and ask for the requirements. Moving on to the free entry museums, here are some list of them that&rsquo;s opened for free: JP Tower Museum Intermediatheque, Advertising Museum Tokyo, Yotsuya Fire Department Museum and (the must-not-miss for anime lovers!) Suginami Animation Museum. Last but not least, you can have a free tour in Suntory Brewery, Kewpie Mayo Terrace, and Mega Web&rsquo;s History Garage (Toyota theme parks).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Dress in Japanese yukata with no charge!</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Feeling incomplete.If you visit Japan without trying the Japanese traditional clothes but hesitant to spend the money for renting or buying it because it isn&rsquo;t cheap? If you find yourself trapped in that situation then hear this: in Tokyo Tourist Information Center, you can wear Japanese traditional clothes like yukata or hakama for FREE. Yes, for free, without any reservations too! The staffs there are ready to help you wear the clothes and you can even borrow some Japanese fans or umbrellas for posing. Well, you can only wear those clothes for taking pictures nearby and just for a while, not for the whole day and no photographer service available either. But considering that you don&rsquo;t have to take out a crazy amount of money for experiencing it already means a lot, right? ;)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Temporary but necessary to know</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some special occasions make it possible for you to have more pleasant memories on your Japan trip. For example if you happened to visit during the right time for sakura blossoms and matsuri (Japanese festival). &nbsp;Matsuri are mostly free entry for everyone. Take a stroll in the matsuri and you&rsquo;ll see the merry atmosphere of Japan. Many food stalls that sell affordable yet tasty food and beverages are lining up with some goods or game stalls in between.It&rsquo;s fine to just take a look around if you don&rsquo;t want to spend any pence, and if you&rsquo;re lucky, you might as well be able to watch some Japanese performances or even hanabi (fireworks). Another example of special occasions is the public holidays in Japan where you can visit the touristic places for free. There are some dates, but one of it is the Tokyo City Day on October 1st. You have to be ready being squished in the crowd though for it tends to get very crowded during holidays.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://livejapan.com/en/article-a0000031/\">https://livejapan.com/en/article-a0000031/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.likealocalguide.com/blog/top-10-best-free-things-to-do-in-tokyo/\">https://www.likealocalguide.com/blog/top-10-best-free-things-to-do-in-tokyo/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://matcha-jp.com/en/5073\">https://matcha-jp.com/en/5073</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(10).jpg', '2019-06-14 16:09:31', b'1', 9, b'1'),
(58, 'Long distance remote surgery to be conducted in the future', 'On June 10th, Japan Health Ministry finally allow remote surgeries in the drafted revised guidelines. Before, such practice is banned by stating that doctors, in principle, must meet their patients at least once in person and are prohibited from performing surgeries on patients unless they’re present in the room.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/pt9HmttxT2x7OGLdld0cMdPZtF9WIaMWDbzyAEYOTFHL2t7cptpq75fxAA1ulLi6AlO2sB26jPi7eFNkDMASXbpRdnN3VJ6axXTU3ibYTxJzAIkTfZLaDWY-241NdHeiyBvc-zvp\" style=\"height:415px; width:624px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On June 10th, Japan Health Ministry finally allow remote surgeries in the drafted revised guidelines. Before, such practice is banned by stating that doctors, in principle, must meet their patients at least once in person and are prohibited from performing surgeries on patients unless they&rsquo;re present in the room.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The so called &ldquo;long distance remote surgery&rdquo; &nbsp;itself is a surgery that uses remote-controlled surgical-aid robots conducted by specialist physicians. With this technology, it&rsquo;d be possible for the surgeon to operate a patient from far away without having to be present on the actual place. To put it simply, a top surgeon in Tokyo can operate a patient in Okinawa without having to transport and present in the surgery room himself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although the revised guidelines are expected to be effective starting July, it would probably take a few years for it to be realized widely. Japan needs to set up the infrastructure first as well as to ensure the safety of such surgery. In correlation with this, the Japan Surgical Society (JSS) reacts quickly by setting up an expert committee to prepare its own guidelines for the practice such as safety procedures and the eligibility of the patients for remote operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/UBJ4ygdnfiguO2Tz9UP4QTVjetbIofNSyCny-eBOteSfF_9qNJlW0hrKFDQfTbeF9NvhH7Jse0m2p15quhuzjQU227KTI-yoCMIKIWH4OUVJSML3vOXlGH2ShHkhiJFcsxFBzYQS\" style=\"height:200px; width:300px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is said that more than 350 US developed surgical-aid robots have been set up throughout Japan. The robot itself is called &ldquo;da Vinci&rdquo; which specializes for remote endoscopic operations. It has a main body with several arms connected by a communication line to another device that&rsquo;s used to operate the main body as well &nbsp;to handle medical instruments used in the operations. There are cameras attached on the tips of the arms to enable physicians to view the images on a monitor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In addition, there are two control devices connected to the main body of da Vinci that can be operated simultaneously. WIth these, the specialist physician outside the room can operate together with the surgeon in charge of the difficult parts of the surgery present in the room. The surgeon himself also functions to continue the surgery if any technical problems occurred.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So far, remote surgeries had just conducted in China on a trial basis and only a few performed elsewhere. If Japan can successfully launch this procedure, it would be a good solution for some problems like severe shortage of surgeons and the critical condition patients who can&rsquo;t afford to travel for the operations. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSource: <a href=\"http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201906130045.html\">http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201906130045.html</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(11).jpg', '2019-06-14 17:18:44', b'1', 4, b'1'),
(59, 'Unique Theme Parks in Japan', 'Unique Theme Parks in Japan', 'GeeksJapan', 'Explore', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">We all know theme parks is the best spot to enjoy some fun time with friends, families and even lover. Usually big names like Disneyland and Universal Studio might be the first to appear in our minds when we&rsquo;re talking about theme parks. However, Japan actually has theme parks with unique concepts which you might never gonna find anywhere else. Therefore why don&rsquo;t you consider to visit some of the theme parks in this list when you visit Japan?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Tokyo DisneySea</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you&rsquo;re a Disneyland lover but have been thriving for more challenging rides or wanting to experience different atmosphere, then this is the right place! Disneyland may exist somewhere else, but not DisneySea. It&rsquo;s an ocean concept theme park which features Disney universe in it which specially established in Japan. DisneySea offers more thrilling rides with of course many &ldquo;splash of water&rdquo; here and there. It might be a bit scary for kids because some of the establishments have &ldquo;dark&rdquo; themes and not to mention the rides themselves are more nerve wracking than the usual Disneyland rides. Youngsters and adults most likely would like this theme park better though.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Chiba</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: around 8.00 am - 10.00 pm (better check it beforehand in the website)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket: 7400 yen (adult), 6400 yen (12-17 years old), 4800 yen (4-11 years old)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website: <a href=\"https://www.tokyodisneyresort.jp/en/tds/\">https://www.tokyodisneyresort.jp/en/tds/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Sanrio Puroland</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Who doesn&rsquo;t know Hello Kitty? This infamous lovable cat character along with her friends are available for &ldquo;meet and greet&rdquo; in this theme park. Just like the cute characters, this theme park looks adorable with many soft-feminine colours that makes it irresistible for photo spots. All the rides here are family friendly, so there won&rsquo;t be any problem for kids or even elders to enjoy it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Tama-Center</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: 9.30 am - 17.00 pm (except closed days)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Weekday: 3300 yen (adult), 2500 (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Holiday: 3800 yen (adult), 2700 yen (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website: <a href=\"https://en.puroland.jp/\">https://en.puroland.jp/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Edo Wonderland Nikko Edomura</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Experience how life in ancient Japanese time is by visiting this Edo setting theme park. Unlike the other theme parks, this place mainly focuses on bringing the atmosphere of the old Japan, therefore the only attraction here that can still be considered as &ldquo;rides&rdquo; is Yakata Boat Cruise. But worry not, they provide many interesting places to visit like ninja house, ninja maze, and dojo where you can try to throw the shuriken or play with the bow and arrows. You could also transform into one of the Edo civilians for a whole day and take as many photos as you like while at it. There are professional fitting staffs available to help you dress up as your desired role ranging from policeman, ninja, princess to samurai and landlord. Spend some time to enjoy the theatrical performances and parade to drown yourself more into the Edo Japanese era.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Nikko</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: 9.00 am - 17.00 pm (summer), 9.30 am - 16.00 pm (winter); close every Wednesday</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket: 4700 yen (adult), 2440 yen (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website:<a href=\"http://edowonderland.net/en/\">http://edowonderland.net/en/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Tokyo Joypolis</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This indoor theme park by SEGA will give you an unforgettable memory as you dive into the VR world and experience it firsthand. There are three floors to explore and satisfy your curiosity. If you&rsquo;re a game lover, don&rsquo;t miss out the chance to &ldquo;get in touch&rdquo; with your favourite games&rsquo; characters here such as the iconic Sonic the Hedgehog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Please note that there are two types of payment system here: admission ticket and passport ticket. If you want to make it simple, just pay for the passport ticket since it already includes admission ticket as well as access to all attractions. But if you just want to play in a few attractions then you better buy the admission ticket and then you can purchase the tickets for your desired attractions later on from the vending machine inside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Odaiba</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: 10.00 am - 10.00 pm (last entry 9.15 pm)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket: 800 yen (adult), 500 yen (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attraction cost: around 500 - 800 yen</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">All inclusive passport price: 4500 yen (adult), 3500 yen (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website: <a href=\"http://tokyo-joypolis.com/language/english/\">http://tokyo-joypolis.com/language/english/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?q=tokyo+joypolis&amp;oq=tokyo+joypolis&amp;aqs=chrome.0.69i59j69i60j0l4.6447j0j7&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8\">https://www.google.com/search?q=tokyo+joypolis&amp;oq=tokyo+joypolis&amp;aqs=chrome.0.69i59j69i60j0l4.6447j0j7&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(12).jpg', '2019-06-18 08:44:03', b'1', 6, b'1'),
(60, 'Traffic signals to function as 5G base stations in Japan', 'In order to accelerate the process to widespread 5G connection across the nation, Japan has planned to make use of the high numbers of traffic lights by turning it into 5G base stations. This plan, written in the government’s draft IT strategy blueprint, is expected to be approved by the cabinet around mid-June. Four major carrier companies, NTT Docomo, KDDI, SoftBank Corp. and Rakuten, aim to invest together with the rough estimation of 1.6 trillion yen over 5 years for this project.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Explore', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/PwAIlKcIw2v2t6I2AmpgRoXrGrNBcSKH77ffDUslNCrG0WGG6i8ogsB0cR1GgXGELOBJzl4jyl6km61mWqBDPFyB-VePpNshX8G-dpzDHKz2X0tor74QkMib636k3EllPp-UWyfL\" style=\"height:351px; width:624px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In order to accelerate the process to widespread 5G connection across the nation, Japan has planned to make use of the high numbers of traffic lights by turning it into 5G base stations. This plan, written in the government&rsquo;s draft IT strategy blueprint, is expected to be approved by the cabinet around mid-June. Four major carrier companies, NTT Docomo, KDDI, SoftBank Corp. and Rakuten, aim to invest together with the rough estimation of 1.6 trillion yen over 5 years for this project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the first place, to cover the whole Japan with 5G would require several hundred thousand base stations. Even if carriers keep on using the existing 4G stations, it&rsquo;s still not enough to accomplish the expected numbers. Additional locations will be necessary to fulfill the target whereas there aren&rsquo;t many available spaces left to build transmissions towers. Usually rooftops are used for this purpose since some areas are lacking vacant land, but the negotiations with landlords aren&rsquo;t as simple as that. For this case, the government decided to allow carriers to use around 200,000 administered traffic signals to fill in as 5G base stations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Government bodies related to this problem (communications ministry, the National Police Agency, the transport ministry and local governments) have planned to set up a council to coordinate the initiative. Tests of 5G equipments on traffic signals are scheduled to run in many cities starting from fiscal 2020 and aimed to be finished introduced all over the country by the end of fiscal 2023.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To make it better, sensors will be installed on the traffic lights for creating &ldquo;trusted mesh networks&rdquo;, a local network that can function even during emergency situations. In other words, despite the connections being cut from the broader internet due to unavoidable reasons, informations can still be transmitted. In accordance, police, carriers and local governments will all have their own private mesh networks too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once applied, it would be possible for local authorities to use the facility to provide better services for the residents. For example during emergency situations, people could scan their My Number identifications cards at base-station-equipped lights to confirm their safety, which would then be informed to their families. Aside from that it could also be used for self-driving vehicle projects, emergency communications in natural disasters and many more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source: <a href=\"https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/5G-networks/Japan-to-greenlight-5G-base-stations-on-200-000-traffic-signals\">https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/5G-networks/Japan-to-greenlight-5G-base-stations-on-200-000-traffic-signals</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(13).jpg', '2019-06-18 09:07:55', b'1', 3, b'1'),
(61, 'Benefits of working in Japan', 'Aside from the fact that you’ve been dying to work in Japan because you’re fond of the culture, food, nature, etc, what other reasons would enlighten others as to why working in Japan is so endearing? Here are some good points which may be a satisfying answer to that question', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">Aside from the fact that you&rsquo;ve been dying to work in Japan because you&rsquo;re fond of the culture, food, nature, etc, what other reasons would enlighten others as to why working in Japan is so endearing? Here are some good points which may be a satisfying answer to that question:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Job security</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Japan is known as a country where the working people are loyal to their companies. Their lifetime devotion to their works are top notch, therefore there&rsquo;s no surprise if the job stability is one of the most important aspects within the Japanese society. Generally, it&rsquo;s not easy for the company to fire employees without any clear cause and evidence. Even during the time of crisis, they&rsquo;d try their best to keep the employees and would rather seek other ways to cut the costs. This point is surely reassuring for employees, as they won&rsquo;t have to worry that much about getting fired when they make a mistake, and it would be a great choice for those who seek a stable job for their entire life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Health insurance</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Japanese company, employees are expected to work very diligently. For that reason, the company will ensure their employees&rsquo; health by providing the health insurance. With this, the employees will get medical treatment with a small fee (or even for &ldquo;free&rdquo; depending on the company&rsquo;s policy) to pay. Not only that, there&rsquo;s also a regular health check up for the employees. This is pretty practical as it will give you a follow up of your health condition and it may as well detect some potential health issues which can be avoided early on since now you&rsquo;ve known it. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Commuter allowance</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Having your transportation expense covered isn&rsquo;t a common thing in every country, that&rsquo;s why it&rsquo;s such a great deal to know that Japanese companies offer this kind of allowance for its employees. What&rsquo;s more exciting is the fact that the so-called teiki (commuter pass) are valid for any parts of train lines in the route to your workplace. This means no matter when you use it even if you&rsquo;re going during weekend, as long as it&rsquo;s still on the covered route, you&rsquo;re not going to be charged for it. Considering the train fees in Japan is not that cheap, having this allowance will certainly helpful to save up your money.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.bulsuk.com/2011/07/top-7-reasons-to-work-for-japanese.html\">https://www.bulsuk.com/2011/07/top-7-reasons-to-work-for-japanese.html</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://blog.gaijinpot.com/5-major-pros-working-japan/\">https://blog.gaijinpot.com/5-major-pros-working-japan/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(14).jpg', '2019-06-18 09:27:26', b'1', 11, b'1'),
(62, 'Different working cultures in Japan', 'While it’s a general knowledge that each country has its own working culture, Japan’s might have been one of the most “unique” of them all.  It’s not rare for foreigners to get a “culture shock” when they first work in Japan or for a Japanese company. Let’s save the judgement on whether it’s good or bad for later, and get to know these differences first:', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While it&rsquo;s a general knowledge that each country has its own working culture, Japan&rsquo;s might have been one of the most &ldquo;unique&rdquo; of them all. &nbsp;It&rsquo;s not rare for foreigners to get a &ldquo;culture shock&rdquo; when they first work in Japan or for a Japanese company. Let&rsquo;s save the judgement on whether it&rsquo;s good or bad for later, and get to know these differences first:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Company&rsquo;s goal before individual&#39;s goal / Company oriented / Company&rsquo;s interest before individual&#39;s interest</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From the first, the company looks out for employees who share the same values with the company itself. The aim is to hire those who can contribute in bringing the company to a higher level than those who seeks for individual achievement or personal development. For this reason, they lack of &ldquo;pigeonholing&rdquo; which lowkey resulted in vague position one would hold. There&rsquo;s always a possibility of getting transferred to another position or division. This might be one of the biggest reasons why self career development is seen as unclear for many. &nbsp;In Japanese society, a stable job is very much preferred. Therefore they have a great pride in working as a part of the company for a long time. Japanese would rather be a part of the company with renowned reputation than having the recognition for their own names. That said, they rely heavily on &ldquo;teamwork&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;one man show&rdquo; and often apply consensus decision making on the actual run, giving spotlight on collective interest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Work all out</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You might have heard this before as news about how devoted Japanese to their work are brought up over and over again. People always points out the long working hours in Japan while comparing it to the working hours in western countries such as the US and Europe. Truthfully, not all those hours are spent for merely working, taking a nap for example is still acceptable. Based on the rules, generally the official working hours is 8 hours per day or 40 hours per week (excluding break). So let&rsquo;s say if the work starts on 8 or 9 am, it should&rsquo;ve ended on 5 or 6 pm. However it is common for Japanese to work overtime for about 1 - 2 hours and the company compensates them for it. Though unwritten, those who work overtime are seen as admirable and not going home before the others do is a form of politeness. Besides the long working hours, some people mentioned about the few amounts of days off received. It is pretty tentative though, and Japan has many national or public holidays too anyway. Other things in line with the point is how the company holds a proper training for their employees and make sure they&rsquo;re doing well. This is a remarkable point considering that not all companies in the world have the same procedure. Some would just &ldquo;throw&rdquo; the new employees to the job and demand them to catch up themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Japanese&rsquo;s politeness</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Japanese is well known for their polite behaviour. However this &ldquo;politeness&rdquo; which they hold dearly might cause misunderstanding especially for foreigners who aren&rsquo;t used to the custom yet. Japanese tend to use indirect communication which means they won&rsquo;t reveal their real intention. They would either go around the topics, stated some reasonings or saying something that has hidden meanings, and they expect you to understand their &ldquo;codes&rdquo;. Saying &ldquo;no&rdquo; or rejecting something directly is viewed as rude. It is also not rare for them to state their wish in disguise. Being confronted is something that Japanese dislike. Even in the workplace, when someone has a problem with his co-worker, he&rsquo;d rather talk to the higher up and let the higher up talk to that co-worker instead of facing him and talk about the problem himself. Better be aware of the &ldquo;unwritten rules&rdquo; or else you might find yourself in unfavourable position. It&rsquo;s hard to list the exact &ldquo;unwritten rules&rdquo;, so you need to observe and learn the custom carefullly. You could ask other senior foreigners or close Japanese friend for</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-indirect communication</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-unwritten rules &gt; need to read between the lines</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-no frontal confrontation &gt; better to report to the higher ups</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Relationship within the company</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-hierarchy &gt; politeness to superior</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-social gathering &gt; drinking culture</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-customer is superior</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Thorough process</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-long decision making</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">-meeting is not discussing but reporting &gt; same goals</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSource: <a href=\"https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2019/01/30/how-tos/thinking-working-japan-good-know-youre/#.XQc5HPwzbIW\">https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2019/01/30/how-tos/thinking-working-japan-good-know-youre/#.XQc5HPwzbIW</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(16).jpg', '2019-06-18 09:29:13', b'1', 12, b'1'),
(63, 'Why Japan is Advanced in Technology?', 'Specifically in terms of workforce automation, Japan is widely known for developing many robots and AI to handle the man’s job. While the other countries still on constant debate for this topic considering the risk of increasing the rate of unemployment, Japan on the other hand has benefited a lot from this. First of all, Japan has been facing the problem of the declining birth rate which impacts on the decline of the number of young people who can be workforces as well. That’s why, having robots and AI to take over the man’s job is seen as a solution to the problem since they can fill in the empty spots or in other words, replace the need of the human workforce. By doing so, it helps boost the productivity of the workers because they can do their jobs more efficiently too. More outcome means more income, and in the bigger case it resulted in the country’s economic growth. Therefore it’s a sure win-win solution.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Tech', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">Technology&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Why Japan is Advanced in Technology?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When we&rsquo;re talking about Japan, we can&rsquo;t avert our attention from the technology topic. New inventions from robots to health related innovations often appear in the news and left us wondering how can Japan be so advanced in technology?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Though there isn&rsquo;t any definite answers to that question because of the complexity in the case itself, we can generally figure it out this way: Japan understands well the power of technology and use it optimally to solve the existing problems. Ever since Japan had realized the importance of technology, they started to strengthen themselves through a lot of development in technological aspect. As the result, nowadays technology seems like an inseparable part of everyday life in Japan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here are some fields in which technology is viewed both as an important for it helps solved many cases as well as highly beneficial&nbsp; to Japan itself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/vqloMTRKhAQ4HoOkthFPp4FqZZQiNcs8fzaRtdJauekwILqEwsOmoOVvt-FtjRYULgFkUg7R0SGQIzfBcdEF54i27PCWfpIWm0l9fICq4x3Yy8CTaBFz3wvS1duEE4s6qYJ2olWl\" style=\"height:318px; width:318px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Infrastructure</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We can&rsquo;t deny that there has been a rapid development in infrastructure area since several decades ago. Shinkansen or the high speed trains for example is one of the well known inventions from Japan.The undeniably fast speed makes it easy for people to commute from suburb to metropolitan area for work. Not only that, it also holds an amazing record for its punctuality and safety. No wonder why it becomes the nation&rsquo;s pride. From the economic point of view, it helps increase the economy in underdeveloped areas because tourists who most likely to visit big cities are drawn to visit the other areas as well considering they wouldn&rsquo;t have to waste their time on the journey with the high speed that Shinkansen has.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/GuvkNGtJl9opzwMp02-E9vbBWl0-u1KnRxfrG3ik5hdUlOtbxOTbP193b3Q2yttXbpYp97XeKD9v7MKnukH5Jo-HU5XxqqCWpESXV5J-VJw8hR0gtWEdEVNH_M17mKBEolvfZS4y\" style=\"height:298px; width:530px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Automation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Specifically in terms of workforce automation, Japan is widely known for developing many robots and AI to handle the man&rsquo;s job. While the other countries still on constant debate for this topic considering the risk of increasing the rate of unemployment, Japan on the other hand has benefited a lot from this. First of all, Japan has been facing the problem of the declining birth rate which impacts on the decline of the number of young people who can be workforces as well. That&rsquo;s why, having robots and AI to take over the man&rsquo;s job is seen as a solution to the problem since they can fill in the empty spots or in other words, replace the need of the human workforce. By doing so, it helps boost the productivity of the workers because they can do their jobs more efficiently too. More outcome means more income, and in the bigger case it resulted in the country&rsquo;s economic growth. Therefore it&rsquo;s a sure win-win solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Environment</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These days, environment labelled as the hot issue in the world. There&rsquo;s a bunch of list concerning this issue such as global warming, pollution, climate change, etc. Best known as a technologically advanced country, Japan has implemented strict regulations based on environmental concerns. Besides, Japan itself has another issue regarding environment: natural disaster. Judging from the geographical point of view, Japan is considered prone to natural disasters like tsunami and earthquakes. Although natural disaster is beyond human capability to control, there&rsquo;s still a way to prevent the worst consequences from happening. For this case, technology has proven to play a big role in solving the problem. Thanks to the advance technology in disaster prevention field, it reduces the number of victims caused by natural disasters and help support the construction for after effect.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSource : <a href=\"http://newsonjapan.com/html/newsdesk/article/124622.php\">http://newsonjapan.com/html/newsdesk/article/124622.php</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(17).jpg', '2019-07-01 13:27:39', b'1', 3, b'1');
