(64, 'What is Working Hours in Japan?', 'We might’ve heard in the news about Japanese people who’s very diligent with their work that he’s even willing to work overtime over and over again for it. Putting aside the tendency of being loyal dan discipline in Japanese themselves,  do you ever wonder how long is the actual working hours in Japan? And what makes these people have to go with working over time countlessly?', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">We might&rsquo;ve heard in the news about Japanese people who&rsquo;s very diligent with their work that he&rsquo;s even willing to work overtime over and over again for it. Putting aside the tendency of being loyal dan discipline in Japanese themselves,&nbsp; do you ever wonder how long is the actual working hours in Japan? And what makes these people have to go with working over time countlessly?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Let&rsquo;s start this by explaining the Japanese working hours system. Basically we can divide the main types of working hours in Japan into three categories:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Fixed time system (固定時間制度, kotei jikan seido)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is the most common type of working hours being used in Japan. In this system there&rsquo;s a fixed schedule: from 8 am - 5 pm or 9 am - 6 pm per day including one hour break time or in short 8 hours per day. In a week, people with this type of system will work from Monday to Friday, so in total they&rsquo;ll have to work for 40 hours per week. The &ldquo;8 hours a day, 40 hours a week&rdquo; are called &ldquo;statutory working hours&rdquo;.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Flexible time system (フレックスタイム制度, furekkusu taimu seido)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This type mostly adopted by designers, design works and IT companies. In this system the person gets to choose freely their start and end time as long as it&rsquo;s still within the range of the agreed working hours and still keep the average time based on the statutory working hours (8 hours a day, 40 hours a week). However, depending on each company&rsquo;s policy, they might as well set a core time in which all employees have to be present in order to secure time to work jointly, run a meetings, etc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Discretionary labor system (裁量労働制度, sairyō rōdō seido)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This type of system oversees the actual working hours because what&rsquo;s counted is whether or not the amount of work given done. In a way this is good because a person can decide personally on how and when to work without being tied by a specific time nor schedule. But the downside of this system is that though it oversees the time, the work must be finished as promised, therefore regardless of the actual amount of time a person has spent, even if he / she works on the weekends or holidays, it&rsquo;s still counted the same. In the worst scenario, such system might lead to excessive overtime working hours.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the official rules (Section 4. Human Resource Management, 4.5 Legislation on working hours, breaks and day off), there are several points that we can highlight:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Working hours must, in principle, not exceed 40 hours per week or eight hours per day excluding breaks (this is known as &ldquo;statutory working hours&rdquo;). However, some businesses are permitted to have their employees work up to 44 hours per week at a maximum of eight hours per day (4.5.1.1)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Employers must grant employees at least one day off per week, or four days off in any four-week period (this is known as &ldquo;statutory days off&rdquo;). Sundays or public holiday need not necessarily be days off, and other days may be selected as employees&rsquo; days off instead by the agreement between the employer and employees. (4.5.1.3)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Companies must pay an increased rate of wages as set forth in the table below* to employees who work in excess of statutory working hours, work on statutory days off or work late at night (between 22:00 - 05.00) (4.5.4)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If we see the result of various questionnaires on overtime hours, majority of the workers confessed that the overtime hours in a month are more than 30 hours, so in average they&rsquo;re working overtime for about 1- 2 hours a day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With all the information above we can conclude that the working hours in Japan still considered fair whether if we view it from the actual regulations or the real implementations itself. Though cases like excessive overtime hours has a possibility to occur, it&rsquo;s not something that most likely happens that often. As long as we know the rules and the limit, and being aware of our own conditions, there shouldn&rsquo;t be a problem with working in Japan. Instead, there might be many things we could learn from Japanese work ethics.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">(*see the actual legislation for details)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.jetro.go.jp/en/invest/setting_up/section4/page5.html\">https://www.jetro.go.jp/en/invest/setting_up/section4/page5.html</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://talenthub.jp/blog/working-in-japan/what-are-working-hours-in-japan/\">https://talenthub.jp/blog/working-in-japan/what-are-working-hours-in-japan/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(18).jpg', '2019-07-04 13:34:01', b'1', 2, b'1'),
(65, 'Why You Should Visit Net Cafe', 'Some of you might’ve heard about net cafe either from watching dorama or reading manga or from a colleague. Now if you wonder why should you visit that place, how about you read our reasonings first', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/v9ZGZaGP7qHCHlm9k1V5NkSw2TfofF2A-5O0Vfu2bBwqUySxOWLinfWhSwdqKNB7ZWwp57207Errlll0R1q_rXGamiiatGVwxbMUpHSKaEdffPiB8JTCMJmlcDrS7-30ZvfFJAeY\" style=\"height:414px; width:414px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some of you might&rsquo;ve heard about net cafe either from watching dorama or reading manga or from a colleague. Now if you wonder why should you visit that place, how about you read our reasonings first:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">It&rsquo;s very affordable yet comfortable</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Net cafe is known to be very affordable in terms of price. Starts from around 100 yen for 30 minutes, 900 - 1500 yen for 3 hours and 1,600 - 3,000 yen for 7 - 12 hours package, net cafe rate is even cheaper than a budget hotel price for staying the night! Fun facts, some people even rent for a week or more, that&rsquo;s why net cafe also has a week package option with tentative price. Net cafe offers many types of seating, from open area seats, semi private booth, to different kind of private rooms. Of course the price will be higher than the open area seats, but it&rsquo;s still affordable considering the privacy you could get from it.&nbsp; What&rsquo;s more, some net cafe separate the smoking area and non smoking area, and it&rsquo;s usually pretty quite (aside from the sound from the keyboard), especially if you rent the private room. With the cozy interior, it&rsquo;d be possible for you to even work here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Easy to find anytime, anywhere</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can find net cafe almost anywhere in Japan. It&rsquo;s a very booming business for it is loved by both youngsters and adults. The fact that it&rsquo;s open for 24 /7 makes it helpful for those who missed the last train or tourists who have short budget. Recently some net cafes also offer a private booth or room with reclining seat, sofa, mattress or even bed to accommodate the needs of people who stays there. This addition makes it comparable to the budget or capsule hotel if not even better considering the services they provide.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Great facilities</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From the basic one: internet services, computer, DVD player, TV, free refill drink, a large collection of manga, comfortable seats or private rooms, to more fancy ones like shower room, laundry room, free snacks / food, locker service, lock (for private rooms), luggage room, and even mailboxes, you can certainly say that this is NOT just a place to get internet or read mangas, but also a worth optional place to stay! Surely these optional services only available in certain net cafes and there&rsquo;re prices to pay too. But it won&rsquo;t be hard to look for one with the facilities that you wished especially nowadays when the business has been developed in a great deal. The &ldquo;little bit higher&rdquo; price worth the facilities anyway, so why the fuss? Probably the only cons is that all those manga are in Japanese and the video / films have hardly any english subtitles. But if you&rsquo;re there to learn Japanese or have understand Japanese well, it won&rsquo;t be of a problem at all.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source : <a href=\"https://www.tsunagujapan.com/there-when-you-need-them-how-to-use-japanese-internet-cafes/\">https://www.tsunagujapan.com/there-when-you-need-them-how-to-use-japanese-internet-cafes/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(19).jpg', '2019-07-08 13:38:59', b'1', 3, b'1'),
(66, 'Hottest Job in Japan #part 2', 'First let us see the result of an annual salary survey by one of the Japanese job sites, DODA (doda.jp), which conducted in 2017. The survey suggests that the average salary in Japan was ￥4,180,000 (around ＄37,192, with the estimation of 1 USD = 112 JPY) with two thirds of the top 30 highest paying jobs are related to Information Technology (IT) and business planning.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/rMYLuFnIeT7Q5Lf7lvzgyG7rbwe9esCJajFrWMxRJfGW5AhCT5zEiDd9t6XI2upB2mtBnGYCFTMdvxPrFxRTHl6K3yOkD0HukbePfPxrpBRGfEXk1bDieso1Pl7BEdS0y7uurGf0\" style=\"height:338px; width:539px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It&rsquo;s not easy to decide the indicators for saying which job is the hottest in Japan at the moment. Especially if we&rsquo;re talking to different audiences : the Japanese and the global. So for now, we let the data talks and view some so-called high demand job for foreigners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">First let us see the result of an annual salary survey by one of the Japanese job sites, DODA (doda.jp), which conducted in 2017. The survey suggests that the average salary in Japan was ￥4,180,000 (around ＄37,192, with the estimation of 1 USD = 112 JPY) with two thirds of the top 30 highest paying jobs are related to Information Technology (IT) and business planning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If we see the types of job said to be in high demand within foreigners, IT professional indeed gets in the list. But aside from that, we&rsquo;ve also narrowed down some jobs that might be in line with your interest:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">IT Professional</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Not only it&rsquo;s considered to have a high salary, this job is on high demand since technology plays a big part in an advanced country like Japan. It professionals like software engineers and programmers are being hire by many Japanese companies and it&rsquo;s not showing any signs of decreasing. In this job, generally your Japanese ability isn&rsquo;t that required so it&rsquo;s pretty convenient for those who aren&rsquo;t a quick learner of Japanese.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Engineer</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Known for its advanced engineering, it&rsquo;s only logical that many Japanese companies are open to hire foreign engineers. From electronics, automotive to heavy industries, Japan sure has many engineering jobs in store for those who crave it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Banker</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Probably just like anywhere else, banker is a common job that&rsquo;s always been a popular choice within the society. Though it isn&rsquo;t a stable environment, some large investment banks have a record of hiring foreign staff to be relocated in Japan. The banking industry itself supports job in the IT sector and pays a great deal. Some even say that the salary for IT staff in investment bank industry is far higher than the one in manufacturing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">English Teacher</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the past this might be the best job for foreigners in Japan since the salary was excellent. Unfortunately, that&rsquo;s not how it works nowadays. Even so, it&rsquo;s still a popular job for foreigners since an English teacher job is always on high demand in Japan and the fact that it doesn&rsquo;t require a proper teaching credentials (unless it&#39;s the Japanese government&rsquo;s JET program) makes the opportunity to join in seems bigger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Service Staff</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are only two basic requirements for working in this job : valid visa and good Japanese language skills. Considering how Japan try their best in expanding the tourism industry, the service staff with bilingual ability is seen as a promising trait. There is no doubt that hotels, resorts, restaurants and cafes in popular tourist area are seeking for individuals with bilingual ability to serve their customers. Now, if you possess those two requirements, why not try and give it a go?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://resources.realestate.co.jp/living/what-are-the-best-paying-jobs-and-industries-in-japan-2018-survey/\">https://resources.realestate.co.jp/living/what-are-the-best-paying-jobs-and-industries-in-japan-2018-survey/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/the-8-most-popular-jobs-for-foreigners-in-japan/\">https://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/the-8-most-popular-jobs-for-foreigners-in-japan/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(20).jpg', '2019-07-11 13:42:29', b'1', 7, b'1'),
(67, 'Experience the attraction in Japan', 'We all know theme parks is the best spot to enjoy some fun time with friends, families and even lover. Usually big names like Disneyland and Universal Studio might be the first to appear in our minds when we’re talking about theme parks. However Japan actually has theme parks with unique concepts which you might never gonna find anywhere else. Therefore why don’t you consider to visit some of the theme parks in this list when you visit Japan?', 'GeeksJapan', 'Explore', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">We all know theme parks is the best spot to enjoy some fun time with friends, families and even lover. Usually big names like Disneyland and Universal Studio might be the first to appear in our minds when we&rsquo;re talking about theme parks. However Japan actually has theme parks with unique concepts which you might never gonna find anywhere else. Therefore why don&rsquo;t you consider to visit some of the theme parks in this list when you visit Japan?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Tokyo DisneySea</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you&rsquo;re a Disneyland lover but have been thriving for more challenging rides or wanting to experience different atmosphere, then this is the right place! Disneyland may exist somewhere else, but not DisneySea. It&rsquo;s an ocean concept theme park which features Disney universe in it which specially established in Japan. DisneySea offers more thrilling rides with of course many &ldquo;splash of water&rdquo; here and there. It might be a bit scary for kids because some of the establishments have &ldquo;dark&rdquo; themes and not to mention the rides themselves are more nerve wracking than the usual Disneyland rides. Youngsters and adults most likely would like this theme park better though.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Chiba</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: around 8.00 am - 10.00 pm (better check it beforehand in the website)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket: 7400 yen (adult), 6400 yen (12-17 years old), 4800 yen (4-11 years old)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website: <a href=\"https://www.tokyodisneyresort.jp/en/tds/\">https://www.tokyodisneyresort.jp/en/tds/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Sanrio Puroland</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Who doesn&rsquo;t know Hello Kitty? This infamous lovable cat character along with her friends are available for &ldquo;meet and greet&rdquo; in this theme park. Just like the cute characters, this theme park looks adorable with many soft-feminine colours that makes it irresistible for photo spots. All the rides here are family friendly, so there won&rsquo;t be any problem for kids or even elders to enjoy it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Tama-Center&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: 9.30 am - 17.00 pm (except closed days)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Weekday: 3300 yen (adult), 2500 (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Holiday: 3800 yen (adult), 2700 yen (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website: <a href=\"https://en.puroland.jp/\">https://en.puroland.jp/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Edo Wonderland Nikko Edomura</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Experience how life in ancient Japanese time is by visiting this Edo setting theme park. Unlike the other theme parks, this place mainly focuses on bringing the atmosphere of the old Japan, therefore the only attraction here that can still be considered as &ldquo;rides&rdquo; is Yakata Boat Cruise. But worry not, they provide many interesting places to visit like ninja house, ninja maze, and dojo where you can try to throw the shuriken or play with the bow and arrows. You could also transform into one of the Edo civilians for a whole day and take as many photos as you like while at it. There are professional fitting staffs available to help you dress up as your desired role ranging from policeman, ninja, princess to samurai and landlord. Spend some time to enjoy the theatrical performances and parade to drown yourself more into the Edo Japanese era.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Nikko</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: 9.00 am - 17.00 pm (summer), 9.30 am - 16.00 pm (winter); close every Wednesday</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket: 4700 yen (adult), 2440 yen (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website:<a href=\"http://edowonderland.net/en/\">http://edowonderland.net/en/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Tokyo Joypolis</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This indoor theme park by SEGA will give you an unforgettable memory as you dive into the VR world and experience it firsthand. There are three floors to explore and satisfy your curiosity. If you&rsquo;re a game lover, don&rsquo;t miss out the chance to &ldquo;get in touch&rdquo; with your favourite games&rsquo; characters here such as the iconic Sonic the Hedgehog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Please note that there are two types of payment system here: admission ticket and passport ticket. If you want to make it simple, just pay for the passport ticket since it already includes admission ticket as well as access to all attractions. But if you just want to play in a few attractions then you better buy the admission ticket and then you can purchase the tickets for your desired attractions later on from the vending machine inside.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Location: Odaiba</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Opening hours: 10.00 am - 10.00 pm (last entry 9.15 pm)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Admission ticket: 800 yen (adult), 500 yen (children)</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attraction cost: around 500 - 800 yen</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">All inclusive passport price: 4500 yen (adult), 3500 yen (children)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Website: <a href=\"http://tokyo-joypolis.com/language/english/\">http://tokyo-joypolis.com/language/english/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?q=tokyo+joypolis&amp;oq=tokyo+joypolis&amp;aqs=chrome.0.69i59j69i60j0l4.6447j0j7&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8\">https://www.google.com/search?q=tokyo+joypolis&amp;oq=tokyo+joypolis&amp;aqs=chrome.0.69i59j69i60j0l4.6447j0j7&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(21).jpg', '2019-07-15 13:45:23', b'1', 2, b'1'),
(68, 'Memorable Cost Free Travel in Tokyo', 'No money? No problem!” is probably the perfect phrase for this case. When you’re short on budget, these worth trying things to do or places to visit in Tokyo can be real saviours that you can’t even believe it costs you nothing. Who says great memories can only be achieved by spending lots of money?', 'GeeksJapan', 'Culture', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/TILQORvZuM5Vu_skwcMdV-JlP4nFR56uqto3FhkRaai0U6ytcg63Nq1a2beFN3GHVR2zS4dn1XBWNVCnC52atQngNu_GEzB9W_I8jMptF9fHgYsXJfV4rm8LfqVWC6UozIvCnNzt\" style=\"height:383px; width:574px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;No money? No problem!&rdquo; is probably the perfect phrase for this case. When you&rsquo;re short on budget, these worth trying things to do or places to visit in Tokyo can be real saviours that you can&rsquo;t even believe it costs you nothing. Who says great memories can only be achieved by spending lots of money?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Public places tourist attractions</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many well known tourist destinations include public places like parks,pedestrian streets or statues located in it .Harajuku, Shibuya, Akihabara and Odaiba for example are actually names of areas where everybody can freely visit. You just need to take note on the iconic places of each area and take photos as the prove. Some of the icons you better put in the list are Hachiko statue, Shibuya crossing, Takeshita dori, Rainbow Bridge, and Gundam statue. Don&rsquo;t forget to check the public parks like Ueno Park, Yoyogi Park, and Tokyo Imperial Palace East Garden where you can freely walk in almost anytime.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Enjoy the scenery with no worry</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Depending on the season, Japan has different sceneries. One of the most favourite scenery is the sakura blossoms in spring, Basically sakura trees can be found in many places across Japan even in streets or housing complex. But many people prefer to gather in public areas like parks to enjoy the beautiful view. This sakura blossoms viewing tradition is called &ldquo;hanami&rdquo;. Of course everyone is free to join in and it&rsquo;s free of charge. Other type of scenery that you can enjoy is the city scape from the skyscraper. While Tokyo Tower or Tokyo Skytree demands you to pay for bucks, you can actually have a free glimpse of the same view from Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building, Carrot Tower, or Bunkyo Civic Center.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Free admission tourist attractions</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some shrines like Meiji Shrine in Harajuku and Sensoji Temple in Asakusa are known for being open to the public without any admission fee, but believe it or not there are also museums, zoo and boat ride that cost you no money too. In Edogawa Ward, there&rsquo;s Edogawa Nature Zoo, a free admission zoo where you can see many adorable animals and even get the chance to pet some of them on the scheduled hours, while in Koto Ward, there&rsquo;s a traditional Japanese wooden boat (wasen) tour along the Yokojikkengawa Canal for about 10 minutes that&rsquo;s offered for free. If you&rsquo;re interested to join the boat tour, just go to the Koto ward office and ask for the requirements. Moving on to the free entry museums, here are some list of them that&rsquo;s opened to public for free: JP Tower Museum Intermediatheque, Advertising Museum Tokyo, Yotsuya Fire Department Museum and (the must-not-miss for anime lovers!) Suginami Animation Museum. Last but not least, you can also have a free tour in Suntory Brewery, Kewpie Mayo Terrace, and History Garage in Mega Web (Toyota theme parks).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Dress in Japanese yukata with no charge!</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Feeling incomplete.If you visit Japan without trying the Japanese traditional clothes but hesitant to spend the money for renting or buying it because of the not-so-cheap price? If you find yourself trapped in that situation then hear this: in Japan National Tourism Organization (JNTO) office, you can wear Japanese traditional clothes like yukata or hakama for FREE. Yes, for free, without any reservations too! The staffs there are ready to help you wear the clothes and you can even borrow some Japanese fans or umbrellas for posing. Well, you can only wear those clothes for taking pictures nearby and just for a while, not for the whole day and no photographer service available either. But considering that you don&rsquo;t have to take out a crazy amount of money for experiencing it already means a lot, right? ;)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Temporary but necessary to know</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some special occasions make it possible for you to have more pleasant memories on your Japan trip. For example if you happened to visit during the right time for sakura blossoms and matsuri (Japanese festival).&nbsp; Matsuri are mostly free entry for everyone. Take a stroll in the matsuri and you&rsquo;ll see the merry atmosphere of Japan. Many food stalls that sell affordable yet tasty food and beverages are lining up with some goods or game stalls in between.It&rsquo;s fine to just take a look around if you don&rsquo;t want to spend any pence, and if you&rsquo;re lucky, you might as well be able to watch some Japanese performances or even hanabi (fireworks). Another example of special occasions is the public holidays in Japan where you can visit the touristic places for free. There are some dates, but one of it is the Tokyo City Day on October 1st. You have to be ready being squished in the crowd though for it tends to get very crowded during holidays.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://livejapan.com/en/article-a0000031/\">https://livejapan.com/en/article-a0000031/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.likealocalguide.com/blog/top-10-best-free-things-to-do-in-tokyo/\">https://www.likealocalguide.com/blog/top-10-best-free-things-to-do-in-tokyo/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://matcha-jp.com/en/5073\">https://matcha-jp.com/en/5073</a>&nbsp;</p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(22).jpg', '2019-07-18 13:48:00', b'1', 5, b'1'),
(69, 'Traffic signals to function as 5G base stations in Japan', 'In order to accelerate the process to widespread 5G connection across the nation, Japan has planned to make use of the high numbers of traffic lights by turning it into 5G base stations. This plan, written in the government’s draft IT strategy blueprint, is expected to be approved by the cabinet around mid-June. Four major carrier companies, NTT Docomo, KDDI, SoftBank Corp. and Rakuten, aim to invest together with the rough estimation of 1.6 trillion yen over 5 years for this project.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Tech', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/PwAIlKcIw2v2t6I2AmpgRoXrGrNBcSKH77ffDUslNCrG0WGG6i8ogsB0cR1GgXGELOBJzl4jyl6km61mWqBDPFyB-VePpNshX8G-dpzDHKz2X0tor74QkMib636k3EllPp-UWyfL\" style=\"height:351px; width:624px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In order to accelerate the process to widespread 5G connection across the nation, Japan has planned to make use of the high numbers of traffic lights by turning it into 5G base stations. This plan, written in the government&rsquo;s draft IT strategy blueprint, is expected to be approved by the cabinet around mid-June. Four major carrier companies, NTT Docomo, KDDI, SoftBank Corp. and Rakuten, aim to invest together with the rough estimation of 1.6 trillion yen over 5 years for this project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the first place, to cover the whole Japan with 5G would require several hundred thousand base stations. Even if carriers keep on using the existing 4G stations, it&rsquo;s still not enough to accomplish the expected numbers. Additional locations will be necessary to fulfill the target whereas there aren&rsquo;t many available spaces left to build transmissions towers. Usually rooftops are used for this purpose since some areas are lacking vacant land, but the negotiations with landlords aren&rsquo;t as simple as that. For this case, the government decided to allow carriers to use around 200,000 administered traffic signals to fill in as 5G base stations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Government bodies related to this problem (communications ministry, the National Police Agency, the transport ministry and local governments) have planned to set up a council to coordinate the initiative. Tests of 5G equipments on traffic signals are scheduled to run in many cities starting from fiscal 2020 and aimed to be finished introduced all over the country by the end of fiscal 2023.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To make it better, sensors will be installed on the traffic lights for creating &ldquo;trusted mesh networks&rdquo;, a local network that can function even during emergency situations. In other words, despite the connections being cut from the broader internet due to unavoidable reasons, informations can still be transmitted. In accordance, police, carriers and local governments will all have their own private mesh networks too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once applied, it would be possible for local authorities to use the facility to provide better services for the residents. For example during emergency situations, people could scan their My Number identifications cards at base-station-equipped lights to confirm their safety, which would then be informed to their families. Aside from that it could also be used for self-driving vehicle projects, emergency communications in natural disasters and many more.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source: <a href=\"https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/5G-networks/Japan-to-greenlight-5G-base-stations-on-200-000-traffic-signals\">https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/5G-networks/Japan-to-greenlight-5G-base-stations-on-200-000-traffic-signals</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(23).jpg', '2019-07-22 13:57:17', b'1', 2, b'1'),
(70, 'Affordable Japanese Clothing Stores', 'Though Japan is more well known for it’s harajuku style in the fashion world, you can actually find many ready-to-wear “normal” clothes shops. What’s even better is that these daily wear clothes come with affordable prices in many stores. Surely you can find H&M and Forever21 stores here, but hey, how about you check out these Japanese clothing brands that won’t lose in terms of price and quality too?', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Though Japan is more well known for it&rsquo;s harajuku style in the fashion world, you can actually find many ready-to-wear &ldquo;normal&rdquo; clothes shops. What&rsquo;s even better is that these daily wear clothes come with affordable prices in many stores. Surely you can find H&amp;M and Forever21 stores here, but hey, how about you check out these Japanese clothing brands that won&rsquo;t lose in terms of price and quality too?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Uniqlo</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Might as well called the most popular affordable clothing store in Japan. Many of the clothes here are the basic necessities to sit in your closet and be that kind of clothes you&rsquo;re going to wear frequently. Uniqlo focuses on basic fashion needs and the comfort of it after all, so there&rsquo;s no way you&rsquo;re not going to use the clothes you&#39;ve bought here. For such practical yet high quality clothes, the prices are thankfully very &ldquo;wallet friendly&rdquo;.&nbsp; Uniqlo often has discounts which marked by red signs, but if you come during weekends, you might encounter more of it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/9fSvGUfpb3nAH-7vixeIX-IZaVgDtr82B-3eQAkgl1t0AdxVFa95iwTch_lndW46pgp4quG0ER-uWN0_1V3n1lvaxyHAHsDSVzC1bOPFKFJaQY2W8TmjKVCXwPvB3PbSza2sNtE1\" style=\"height:235px; width:460px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">GU</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you don&rsquo;t fancy the plain clothes in Uniqlo, you might like this one. Owned by the same company as Uniqlo, GU displays more trendy clothes in the store, with surprisingly cheaper price. No wonder why it&rsquo;s the youngsters&rsquo; favourite. With 280 stores operated throughout the country, you won&rsquo;t find any difficulties to spot one and shop there. Moreover there&rsquo;s a bunch of discounts too waiting in GU that you might not want to miss.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/rhdlUgtwW_FIqfFkOxuEUep3622wbkVncjKcA0Sy3DjanH9FKlruqOFpQY8cWav6y8scmohWfoITPX7nRriNGnZzqGUzT89dll45B7h6anhcs6b4KKlfU2p-jHUWEcZucixeMGVL\" style=\"height:290px; width:420px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Honeys</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Normally you can find this brand in AEON group shopping malls. Not only it has around 800 stores in Japan, this brand also release several clothing lines such as Cinema Club, Honeys Club, Golza, etc, to suit the taste of many generations. Honeys sells trendy clothes and never bored to excite you with big discounts. When you shop here, don&rsquo;t be surprised to find a complete yukata set with obi and geta for only around 3500 yen!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/Mta2WzoVwmFHD4VEDJBdG4aFCBK7kIe1VHpfEsD1YOJmCr6TiP-ipENJpF9cIDZsh-lip_92Wo2uuDQGXOi-T9nGPOPP10ZyCI6jki-hj8qhmepCAIIbFRgxD5Qr2MCUxeIp1PJj\" style=\"height:345px; width:518px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">WEGO</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">First established in Shibuya, Tokyo, this brand has now expanded and hit the amount of 150 stores nationwide. Bringing the style from the renowned fashion districts in Japan, Shibuya and Harajuku, in their designs, this casual ready-to-wear clothing brand easily gained favour from the youth. Not to mention they sell these fashionable clothes at affordable prices. For sure you wouldn&rsquo;t want to miss checking this brand, right?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/PV4bHlFzs9mtJA2aJASJBqc1vf3yoUMpXMwdNn5lsy797Jleonr7sdBkaZJRvZqrFEfVa3OnNTNJQY1G4VGl34uhwyKbplhBS1xFIFl3i_UZ48LnUiFFd-awWIXPVKrkQS_xLIjF\" style=\"height:308px; width:464px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Shimamura</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In terms of amount, Shimamura wins the bet by scoring around 1,300 stores across Japan. With its widespread, there&rsquo;s a high chance to shop from here even if you live in the countryside. The average prices in the store is more or less 1000 yen. They even provide affordable clothes for babies too! Although their designs might not be as trendy as the previous brands, Shimamura nowadays are working on keeping up with the trends. During New Year, there&rsquo;s a &ldquo;Lucky Bag&rdquo; tradition in Japan where shops sell goodie bags with a bunch of random items stuffed there for an affordable price. Try to buy a Lucky Bag from Shimamura and you&rsquo;ll find it as a very great deal.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://jw-webmagazine.com/5-clothing-stores-in-japan-to-shop-cheap-look-rich-9f878e06c49a\">https://jw-webmagazine.com/5-clothing-stores-in-japan-to-shop-cheap-look-rich-9f878e06c49a</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://japanesestation.com/tampil-cantik-dengan-harga-murah-meriah-di-tokyo/\">https://japanesestation.com/tampil-cantik-dengan-harga-murah-meriah-di-tokyo/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(24).jpg', '2019-07-25 14:00:42', b'1', 3, b'1'),
(71, 'Best Inexpensive Lifestyle Shops in Japan', 'Ever heard of Japan as one of the highest living cost countries in the world? Well guess what, rejoice~ We’ve found a solution for your daily needs: the inexpensive lifestyle shops! These shops below sells products in unbelievably inexpensive price. Most of the stuff they sell are under 500 yen! Wait no more and read this:', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ever heard of Japan as one of the highest living cost countries in the world? Well guess what, rejoice~ We&rsquo;ve found a solution for your daily needs: the inexpensive lifestyle shops! These shops below sells products in unbelievably inexpensive price. Most of the stuff they sell are under 500 yen! Wait no more and read this:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">100 yen shops</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We can&rsquo;t start this list without mentioning the king of 100 yen shop, Daiso. You can find this shop almost everywhere which is very reassuring since it&rsquo;d most likely get your daily necessities covered up. Next in line, there&rsquo;s Seria, a 100 yen shop that selects its products to make sure only the high quality ones will be sold. This store gets positive reviews for its spacious and tidy interior and of course for its stylish products. The biggest rival for Seria as the &ldquo;fashionable 100 yen shop&rdquo; is Can Do. Can Do&rsquo;s put attention to its products&rsquo; designs which is also applied in its affiliated shop, Le Plus. Natural Kitchen might be an underrated name in this group, but they have cute and feminine high quality products ready to compete with the other big names. Though Natural Kitchen isn&rsquo;t necessarily a 100 yen shop, the fact that most of their products are sold at 100 yen worth mentioning in this group.&nbsp; If you don&rsquo;t really mind about designs, Watts might get a check from you. Watts put practical use and affordable price (100 yen) as its main concern, but unfortunately not for the looks. Last on this group is the Lawson Store 100. Different than the others, Lawson Store 100 offers fresh groceries but still in the same concept of 100 yen shop.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">300 yen shops</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Moving on to 300 yen shops, the first on the list is 3Coins. This shop has a wide variety of items with colour palettes that&rsquo;s tempting to be bought as a match. Under the same wings, Smart LIfe Market is more popular with families since it has more &ldquo;natural&rdquo; vibes and available in suburban areas. A rising competitor for 3Coins group, illusie300 proves less in terms of store&rsquo;s amounts doesn&rsquo;t mean it&rsquo;s less in terms of products. Displaying fancy designs, you can even take some chopsticks or napkins from illusie300 as souvenirs. Amongst all, the cute character items and accessories shop, Mikazuki Momoko stands out as the most &ldquo;kawaii&rdquo; 300 yen shop. Not only it has a lovable mascot, Momoko-chan, this shop frequently collaborates with brands like Sanrio for a level up to their products.Design-wise however CouCou comes in the first place. You can&rsquo;t even believe CouCou is a 300 yen shop based on the items only because it looks much more expensive than that. It&rsquo;s undeniably charming which makes it irresistible to not bring some home.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Still under 500 yen&nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sankyuu Mart has an interesting name. The word &lsquo;sankyuu&rdquo; is the informal speech of &ldquo;thank you&rdquo;, adapted right from the Englilsh word itself. On the other side, &ldquo;san&rdquo; in Japanese means &ldquo;three&rdquo; while &ldquo;kyuu&rdquo; means &ldquo;nine&rdquo;. This is probably the biggest reason why it chooses 390 yen as the fixed price in the shop (excluding tax). Yup, Sankyuu Mart is a 390 yen secondhand shop which originated from Harajuku. Though secondhand, the items are fashionable without question. You can expect no less from a fashion district origin shop anyways. The same goes for Rainbow Spectrum that&rsquo;s located in Shibuya, another infamous fashion district in Japan. From the name alone, you could guess this shop is filled with colourful vibes creating a party atmosphere in the air. It&rsquo;s not a fixed price shop but there are bountiful items labelled under 500 yen. Still in Shibuya, Awesome Store lives up to its name by offering affordable trendy items in the garage like shop. Ranging from 200 - 400 yen only, you&rsquo;ll find yourself in a dilemma for choosing which item to buy from the miscellaneous line ups. Coming from neighboring city, Asoko joins in the group with competitive price (mostly around 100-300 yen) and a wide variety of products. In this store, both men and women can enjoy the collection of things from cute to cool.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A friendly reminder, it is important to check out the price tag even if you enter the fixed price shops. Although they are titled &ldquo;100 yen or 300 yen shop&rdquo;, there&rsquo;s always a possibility that some products labelled with higher prices as well. Most fixed price shops also haven&rsquo;t included the tax, but in some places like a few selected Daiso shops, they have a tax-free corner for foreigners to refund the tax. Last but not least, have a pleasant shopping experience~</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.timeout.com/tokyo/shopping/the-best-100-shops-in-tokyo\">https://www.timeout.com/tokyo/shopping/the-best-100-shops-in-tokyo</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://www.tsunagujapan.com/7-recommended-300-yen-shop-in-tokyo/\">https://www.tsunagujapan.com/7-recommended-300-yen-shop-in-tokyo/</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://planetexp.com/shop/100-yen-shop/\">https://planetexp.com/shop/100-yen-shop/</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://jw-webmagazine.com/all-the-high-quality-brands-of-100-yen-shops-in-japan-b6d19cb4e067\">https://jw-webmagazine.com/all-the-high-quality-brands-of-100-yen-shops-in-japan-b6d19cb4e067</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://livejapan.com/id/article-a0000546/\">https://livejapan.com/id/article-a0000546/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(25).jpg', '2019-07-29 14:03:34', b'1', 4, b'1');
