(72, 'Basic guide to buy train tickets in Japan', 'Train has been part of everyday life in Japan, whether going to work, school, or even for vacation, everyone rides on trains. The railway lines in Japan are pretty much practical in helping us to reach whenever we want in a short time, in addition it is known for being clean and neat. No wonder why Japanese take pride in their trains, and foreigners are eager to experience travelling in Japanese train.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/yRm8Gyf0Q6Ao7vau06Aa96pjEdH9eCcpEZ5MepeUPIVrmZhSB113-Pfv52qtG7Bf-8A8y78a27QqghzIIrj8glLPkXHtvN-91Ruc1YDb0CRLyTaaWwzhfqYf-FgLI4qVmrrcRBZm\" style=\"height:357px; width:535px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Train has been part of everyday life in Japan, whether going to work, school, or even for vacation, everyone rides on trains. The railway lines in Japan are pretty much practical in helping us to reach whenever we want in a short time, in addition it is known for being clean and neat. No wonder why Japanese take pride in their trains, and foreigners are eager to experience travelling in Japanese train.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Now if you want to ride a train, you&rsquo;ll need to purchase a ticket. Basically there are three types of tickets or pass that could get you on a train : IC card, Japan Rail Pass and regular ticket. You can see the details of each type in the table below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Type</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Ticket</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">IC Card</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Japan Rail Pass</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">For whom</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Everyone</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Everyone</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Tourist only</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Duration</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">One trip only</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Unlimited but can be invalid if it&#39;s not used within 10 years</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">1 - 3 weeks</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Used for</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Depend on the type (train / subway / shinkansen, etc)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Train, subway, bus, and a few shinkansen</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Train and shinkansen (except Nozomi and Mizuho)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Covered area</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Depend on the trip</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">All</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Depend on JR Pass type (East / West)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Price</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Depend on the trip</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">500 yen refundable deposit + initial amount (usually 1500 yen in total)&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Start from around 30,000 yen (adult) or 15,000 yen (children)</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Where to buy</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Ticket machines or ticket counter in stations</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Ticket machines or ticket counter in selected stations</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p dir=\"ltr\">Online, travel agent in foreign countries and few selected stations in Japan</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Regular train ticket is the best choice if you just want to try riding on a train in Japan for once. If you have JR Pass, you&rsquo;ll also have to buy the subway tickets since it&rsquo;s not included. For buying regular ticket, the easiest way is to get it from the ticket machines in the station. The ticket machine usually has an English language option and you can purchase it by inserting coins or bills. In general the machine accepts money in forms of 10, 50, 100 yen coins or 1000 yen bills, but some also accept larger bills. There&rsquo;s an option to buy tickets from the ticket counter too in case you can&rsquo;t use the machine. If you&rsquo;ve decided to buy the ticket via ticket counter, be ready to prepare these informations or better write it down and show it to the staff:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Number of travelers</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Date of travel</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Departure station</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Destination station</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Seat category(ordinary or green car)</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Preference of reserved or non-reserved seat</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The last two points above might confuse you, so simply saying, some Japanese trains have different category for seating: ordinary and green car, and there are some trains that require reservations first. Green car is like the first class seat, less crowded and provides reclining seats. There&rsquo;s a special wait lane in the platform for green car passengers. To ride in green car area, you need to make reservations. Seat reservation roughly cost you around 300 - 700 yen. In some shinkansen and limited express trains, advanced reservations are also necessary. That&rsquo;s why you better recheck your train route plan beforehand to avoid misinformations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">JR Pass is a very convenient choice if you travel for a short while and wanting to ride on trains without any hassle. Aside from subway tickets like Tokyo Metro or Toei Subways, almost all types of train tickets (shinkansen too!) are included as long as it is within the covered area of your JR Pass type (East or West). Even if it excludes Nozomi and Mizuho shinkansen, you can actually still go on the same route using different types of shinkansen which is a bit slower in speed (but you&rsquo;ll get there anyway, so no worries). Another advantage from having JR Pass is that you don&rsquo;t have to pay for making reservations to ride shinkansen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The top choice amongst these three might be IC card. Whether you&rsquo;re going to use it for a short or long time stay, it has your back. As long as your IC card is one of the ten main IC cards in Japan, it can function just fine in wherever any of the others is issued. To get a new IC card, simply just buy it from the IC card machine located in selected stations. This machine can also be used for to up later on. The maximum amount in IC card is 20,000 yen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">IC card has a wide range of usage from riding trains, subways, and buses to act like a payment card in several shops, vending machines or even parking lot. However there are also some limitations in using IC card, such as you can&rsquo;t use it for purchasing highway bus&rsquo; tickets nor travelling directly across different areas (for example from Tokyo to Nagoya). For the record, you can ask to refund the 500 yen deposit along with unused credit from the card by bringing it to the issuing company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To avoid confusion, only IC card and regular ticket holder can pass through automatic gate. For IC Card, just a tap is enough, while for the ticket, you need to put it inside the ticket slot . For the entry, the paper ticket will appear again on the other side, so don&rsquo;t forget to pick it up after you pass the automatic barricade because you&rsquo;ll need it again for getting out of your destination station later. JR Pass holder will have to go through manned gate and show his pass to the station staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A helpful tip: download hyperdia app to check out the train details (schedule, train numbers, platform, price, etc). May you have a memorable trip~</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://matcha-jp.com/en/2689\">https://matcha-jp.com/en/2689</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://www.japan-guide.com/e/e2016.html\">https://www.japan-guide.com/e/e2016.html</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://matcha-jp.com/en/1349\">https://matcha-jp.com/en/1349</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://matcha-jp.com/en/30\">https://matcha-jp.com/en/30</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://www.japan-guide.com/e/e2359_003.html\">https://www.japan-guide.com/e/e2359_003.html</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://www.japanvisitor.com/japan-travel/prepaidcard\">https://www.japanvisitor.com/japan-travel/prepaidcard</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(26).jpg', '2019-08-01 14:36:53', b'1', 4, b'1'),
(73, 'Basic Japanese Medicines', 'Living abroad will always have its very own “surprises” every here and then. Not all the surprises are pleasing to encounter though, and one of them is when you happen to feel unwell.This matter becomes more serious as medicines in different countries can be so much different which is prone to drive you into confusion and panic state. Before anything of some sort happens, let’s learn the basic medicines in Japan to keep you in line during that unfavourable times', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Living abroad will always have its very own &ldquo;surprises&rdquo; every here and then. Not all the surprises are pleasing to encounter though, and one of them is when you happen to feel unwell.This matter becomes more serious as medicines in different countries can be so much different which is prone to drive you into confusion and panic state. Before anything of some sort happens, let&rsquo;s learn the basic medicines in Japan to keep you in line during that unfavourable times:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Multifunctions painkillers</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Headache and cramps are probably the mainstream health problems that many would suffered from. No wonder why these medicines easily gained popularity within the Japanese society. For starters Bufferin and Eve are two painkillers brands that are widely known. While Bufferin is stomach friendly, Eve has no nasty after taste as its plus point. These two has several types of painkillers for more specific causes, but if you&rsquo;re confused, just choose &ldquo;A&rdquo; variant as its the standard one. Another popular brand is Loxonin S which is also useful for muscle pain, ear pain, bruises, broken bones and sprains. However since it&rsquo;s stronger than the other two, it might affect your stomach and not recommended for those with allergies.For the picture, Loxonin S price starts from 648 yen / 12 tablets.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Comfort your stomach</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When you haven&rsquo;t eaten anything yet your stomach is in pain, Gaster 10 is ready to help. Specializing in gastrointestinal problems, heartburn and repugnance, Gaster 10 comes in tablets, powder and mini pills that doesn&rsquo;t require water to consume for 1580 yen / 12 tablets. For curing diarrhea from chilled sleep or over eating / drinking, Lopera mac satto might be a good choice. Its tablet dissolves once you put it in the mouth and is sold for 950 yen / 6 tablets. If you want something more authentic and don&rsquo;t mind strong smelled medicine, try Oota Isan or Seirogan instead. Seirogan is actually pretty handy when it comes to functions since it handles water or food poisoning, vomiting and toothache cases too. Unfortunately this small black ball shaped medicine has a strong smell and aftertaste which isn&rsquo;t to everyone&rsquo;s liking. The same goes for Oota Isan, a powder medicine that first trials might find&nbsp; it challenging on how to swallow. Stored in a small packages or a can, Oota Isan is a herbal medicine anyway, so it&rsquo;s of no surprise to have such a strong smell, right?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Get over cold related sickness</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Next in the list is the cold related sickness. Ranging from sneezing, coughing, phlegm, mucus to fever, chills, headache and body aches, medicines to fight such sickness are definitely a must-have item for emergencies. Generally, Ryukakusan direct is capable as a throat lozenges. Contains herbal ingredients, this medicine dissolves once eaten. You can choose to consume mint or peach flavoured powder (packed in small portions) or mango flavoured pills for this brand. Based on popularity, Pabulon and Lulu attack ex topped the rank in this group. Pabulon aims to put off sickness before it turns into cold. This brand offers small package powder variant and a package of yellow pills (starts from 1700 yen for 28 pills). Lulu attack ex on the other hand has only one variant, white coloured pills which are easy to swallow. Other options for this case includes Esutakku Ibufine and Kakkonto. However please note that Kakkonto is a herbal medicine with distinctive smell which should be avoided for those with frailness or perspiration issue. People usually consumed Kakkonto when they&rsquo;re on the early stage of cold. There are several types like small powder pack, bottled liquid and pills with the starting price of 1480 yen per 15 capsules.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Precautions for hangover&nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Drinking culture has engraved deeply in Japanese society. It is common to have a booze after work with colleagues and normally every party even the small ones include alcohol in the menu. Therefore, hangover is a risk to be expected and better be anticipated. You can easily find hangover medicines in health or drink section in convenience store. Usually they&rsquo;re sold in the form of bottled liquid, but another variants also available like Ukon no chikara offers small pack powder, No mikata offers small stick pack of granules form, while Heparize offers pills variant. Preferably consume this type of medicine before taking alcohol to prevent hangover. But based on the present condition, you might as well consume it during the drinking occasions or later as a treatment to hangover.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">For insect caused and more</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Theoretically speaking, for a country that&rsquo;s famous for it nature, insect related problem is not something new. Kinkan and Muhi are two most familiar names when it comes to&nbsp; medicine to cure insect related problems. Both provides external use liquid medicine that can be applied directly to the &ldquo;problematic area&rdquo;. But it&rsquo;s worth to know that they can do more than that. Kinkan for example can be used for healing itches, shoulder and hip pain, bruises and sprains. And Muhi which has another variant of a tube paste medicine, is applicable too for treating rashes eczema, frost bite, dermatitis and even inflammation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\">Others</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The medicines in this group are pretty useful yet optional since everyone basically faces different health problems. You might not feel the need to have these but nevertheless it&rsquo;s not hurt to know. Sante is a reccommended brand for eye drop with many variants of it to suit your needs.Of course the main task of them is to help ease the eye related problems such as eye fatigue. Last in the list is Sakamukea, a bandage&nbsp; in the form of liquid that might surprise some people at first glance. Get to know it better though and you&rsquo;ll find it very useful. Just put the liquid on the desired area and it will dry quickly and stay put. SInce it&rsquo;s transparent, and light in texture, it creates an illusion of &ldquo;not using any bandage at all&rdquo;. Isn&rsquo;t it awesome?</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Source:</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.tsunagujapan.com/6-medicines-to-buy-in-japanese-convenience-stores/\">https://www.tsunagujapan.com/6-medicines-to-buy-in-japanese-convenience-stores/</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://www.tsunagujapan.com/a-guide-japanese-otc-medicine-for-travelers/\">https://www.tsunagujapan.com/a-guide-japanese-otc-medicine-for-travelers/</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://itsyourjapan.com/medication-in-japan/\">https://itsyourjapan.com/medication-in-japan/</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://jw-webmagazine.com/7-useful-medicines-you-can-find-in-japan-db4091061f90\">https://jw-webmagazine.com/7-useful-medicines-you-can-find-in-japan-db4091061f90</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://jw-webmagazine.com/7-essential-medicines-in-japan-which-will-save-your-life-54c7d8d7e675\">https://jw-webmagazine.com/7-essential-medicines-in-japan-which-will-save-your-life-54c7d8d7e675</a><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://livejapan.com/en/article-a0002423/\">https://livejapan.com/en/article-a0002423/</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(27).jpg', '2019-08-06 13:33:41', b'1', 4, b'1'),
(74, 'As Japan frets about dearth of AI talent, Daikin develops its own program', 'There’s a sense of panic within Japan Inc and the government - the world’s No. 3 economy doesn’t have enough experts in artificial intelligence and it’s time to do something about it.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Tech', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>By Tetsushi KajimotoOSAKA</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s a sense of panic within Japan Inc and the government - the world&rsquo;s No. 3 economy doesn&rsquo;t have enough experts in artificial intelligence and it&rsquo;s time to do something about it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SoftBank Group Corp CEO Masayoshi Son last month bemoaned the state of play, calling Japan a &quot;developing country&quot; in the most important current tech revolution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prime Minister Shinzo Abe in June unveiled a plan to train 250,000 people in AI skills annually by 2025, albeit one criticized as unrealistic due to a shortage of teachers. Tech heavyweights like Sony Corp are hiking pay for the right hires and boosting recruitment of foreign engineers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Daikin Industries Ltd, the world&rsquo;s biggest maker of air conditioners with a market value of $37 billion, is taking a more unusual route to AI expertise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At a disadvantage to bigger tech firms in attracting top talent, it has created an in-house program that takes new graduates and current employees - almost all with no AI background - and trains them up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It aims to make 1,000 employees AI-savvy by 2022, in what Daikin says is one of the most ambitious AI-specific training programs by a Japanese company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We have a sense of crisis as we don&rsquo;t have experts well-versed in information technology when AI and data analysis are in great demand,&rdquo; Yuji Yoneda, executive officer at Daikin&rsquo;s Technology and Innovation Center, told Reuters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daikin sees AI as essential to its future business model, in which it plans to offer subscription services with AI-powered air conditioners adjusting the temperature and quality of air autonomously to improve efficiency in factories and households.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Just as car makers are promoting the concept of mobility as a service, we will promote air as a service by providing various services related to air,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New hires get the most training with a two-year program. The first crop of 100 graduates hired last year took classes given by Osaka University professors for about six months, with the rest of their first year spent on data analysis and group work. This year, they have been assigned to various departments for on-the-job AI training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daikin declined to comment on the cost of its program.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By comparison, Sony offers its engineers 290 courses, including AI-courses, that range from a few hours to several days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daikin is also keen to hire more engineers from India and China but says its struggles in the United States where it needs to offer hundreds of thousands of dollars to attract the graduates it wants. Additionally, it is looking at raising pay for AI experts to keep them loyal to the company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Japan&rsquo;s AI woes can be overstated. Of the top 20 companies in AI patents, 12 are Japanese, according to the World Intellectual Property Organization&rsquo;s 2019 report on technology trends. These include Toshiba, NEC Corp, Panasonic Corp, Sony and Toyota Motor Corp.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But compared to the United States, which issued a national AI development plan in 2016, and China which unveiled plans in 2017 to become a global leader in AI by 2025, Japan is lagging.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Combined Japanese government and corporate investment in information and communication technology was 16.3 trillion yen ($150 billion) in 2017, up 12% from 1994, Japanese government data showed. By contrast, U.S. investment in the sector more than tripled over the same period to $655 billion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Japanese universities have also come under fire for not doing enough in AI and data science education. The industry ministry estimates Japan had a shortage of 220,000 IT workers in 2018, which could deepen to 790,000 in 2030 - a prediction that was part of the impetus for Abe&rsquo;s plan to train 250,000 people in AI annually.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In contrast, the World Intellectual Property Organization report noted that Chinese organizations make up 17 of the top 20 academic players in AI patenting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hitoshi Matsubara, vice president of Future University Hakodate and an expert in AI, says Japan needs to invest more, make IT jobs more attractive and shake off the mindset that most employees of the same age should be treated equally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;In Japan, IT jobs have long been thought of as labour-intensive with low pay and late-night work. If they are as well-paid and rewarding as in the United States and China, information science would become more popular among students,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That is starting to change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year, Sony began to offer starting salaries of up to 7.3 million yen for postgraduates proficient in areas such as AI, compared with its standard starting salary of 6 million yen. Toshiba also overhauled its pay system, allowing it to offer bigger salaries to people with expertise in AI and the Internet of Things.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chat app operator Line Corp, which is diversifying into fintech and AI, also boosted annual pay to top graduates to as much as 8 million yen compared to 5.5 million yen for lower-skilled engineers. It is also a heavy recruiter of foreign engineers, who account for 37% of its 670 engineers in Japan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sony too is casting its net wider, with favored recruitment grounds including Carnegie Mellon University, Tsinghua University and Indian Institute of Technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Competition in hiring IT talent - whether new grads, mid-career and foreign workers - is getting tougher and tougher,&rdquo; says Kazunari Ikeyama, a manager in Sony&rsquo;s human resources division. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re broadening our focus, not just in Japan but also globally.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nsource :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://japantoday.com/category/tech/As-Japan-frets-about-dearth-of-AI-talent-Daikin-develops-own-program\">https://japantoday.com/category/tech/As-Japan-frets-about-dearth-of-AI-talent-Daikin-develops-own-program</a></p>', 'Living_Cost_in_Japan_(28).jpg', '2019-08-08 11:03:53', b'1', 1, b'1'),
(75, 'Portable fans a breath of fresh air in sweltering summer heat', 'As Japan\'s unrelenting summer heat continues, people young and old are resorting to a creative way to stay cool: portable electric fans of various colors, sizes and functions that are becoming a hit item to beat the heat.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Life', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>By Junko HoriuchiTOKYO</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As Japan&#39;s unrelenting summer heat continues, people young and old are resorting to a creative way to stay cool: portable electric fans of various colors, sizes and functions that are becoming a hit item to beat the heat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stores selling the fans, some of which conveniently attach to the neck or wrist, say the products are selling at a brisker pace than last year, becoming the latest trend in ways to cope with elevated temperatures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While the fans were notably popular among younger women last year, the deadly summer heat in Japan -- which has resulted in a number of deaths in recent weeks -- has also prompted men and women of all ages to seek them for a blast of cool air.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have many products to fight heat, such as foldable fans, cool sprays and cool bandanas, but this year the portable fans are the most popular among such items. It has become a norm in the Japanese summer,&quot; Kazuyuki Yamada, a spokesman at Tokyu Hands Inc in its lifestyle department, said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For this season, the household goods store has been selling some 100 different types of handheld portable fan since April, around double that of the year before. As of Aug 8, Tokyu Hands&#39; stores nationwide had sold 180,000 units of the products, a threefold increase from 2018.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fans, some as light as 80 grams and mostly carrying a price tag of 1,500 yen to 2,000 yen, feature various functions, including a mobile battery charger, wind power adjustments and aroma diffusers. Many of them are foldable with clips that can be attached to bags or tables.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the hot ticket item this year is a fan that can be strapped around the user&#39;s neck, Yamada said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The ones with light-emitting diodes, which were newly introduced this year, can be used in the dark such as at fireworks festivals. YouTubers who do not want to be sweating when filming outdoors are buying them, too,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interior goods retailer Franfran Corp has developed new models of portable fans with reduced wind sound and more power after selling over 100,000 fans from April to August last year. This year, it had sold 600,000 units as of Aug 8, nearly a sixfold increase.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Consumers are using the fans everywhere, when commuting, during sports or at home, for instance after taking a bath,&quot; said Aya Shimomura, a spokeswoman for Franfran. &quot;Interestingly, some parents are using it to cool food such as for babies.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The popularity of the portable fans reminds me of the mini-heater or mini-humidifier for use on desktops that were a hit in the winter season,&quot; Shimomura said. &quot;It shows that more people are looking to create a comfortable personal space as how one feels about temperature differs from person to person. Some people are more adaptable to heat or cold than others.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retailers hope that the portable fans will also be used by foreign tourists visiting Japan for the Rugby World Cup starting in September and the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics kicking off in July next year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also the recent boom of outdoor activities, such as camping, music festivals and comic-related events called Comiket, are expected to further boost demand for portable fans, shop operators say.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far this summer, Japan has experienced similar temperatures to the extreme heat that gripped the archipelago last summer, with many observation points nationwide registering temperatures of 35 C or above.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the week starting July 29, 57 people died due to heat-related medical issues across the country. The number taken to hospitals more than tripled from the previous week&#39;s 5,664 to 18,347, the second highest since tallies began in 2008, according to the Fire and Disaster Management Agency.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>source :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://japantoday.com/category/business/feature-portable-fans-a-breath-of-fresh-air-in-sweltering-summer-heat\">https://japantoday.com/category/business/feature-portable-fans-a-breath-of-fresh-air-in-sweltering-summer-heat</a></p>', 'Escape_to_the_country_(1).jpg', '2019-08-12 10:31:58', b'1', 4, b'1'),
(76, 'Library of spider silk could hold secrets for new materials', 'With two pairs of fine-tipped tweezers and the hands of a surgeon, Cheryl Hayashi began dissecting the body of a silver garden spider under her microscope.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Tech', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With two pairs of fine-tipped tweezers and the hands of a surgeon, Cheryl Hayashi began dissecting the body of a silver garden spider under her microscope.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In just a few minutes she found what she was seeking: hundreds of silk glands, the organs spiders use to make their webs. Some looked like mashed potatoes, others like green worms or air-filled rubber gloves. Each lets the spider produce a different type of silk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some silk types can be stretchy, others stiff. Some dissolve in water, others repel it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They make so many kinds of silk!&quot; Hayashi said. &quot;That&#39;s just what boggles my mind.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hayashi has collected spider silk glands of about 50 species, just a small dent in the more than 48,000 spider species known worldwide. Her lab at the American Museum of Natural History is uncovering the genes behind each type of silk to create a sort of &quot;silk library.&quot; It&#39;s part of an effort to learn how spiders make so many kinds of silk and what allows each kind to behave differently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The library could become an important storehouse of information for designing new pesticides and better materials for bullet-proof vests, space gear, biodegradable fishing lines and even fashionable dresses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hayashi has been at this for 20 years, but improved technology only recently let scientists analyze the DNA of silk faster and produce artificial spider silk in bulk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Any function that we can think of where you need something that requires a lightweight material that&#39;s very strong, you can look to spider silk,&quot; Hayashi said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spider silks all start out the same: a wad of goo, akin to rubber cement or thick honey, as Hayashi describes it. Spiders make and stash it in a gland until they want to use the silk. Then, a narrow nozzle called a spigot opens. And as the goo flows out, it morphs into a solid silk strand that is weaved with other strands emerging from other spigots.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nobody knows how many kinds of spider silks exist, but some species can produce a variety. Orb-weaving spiders, for example, make seven types. One has a sticky glue to catch prey. Another is tough but stretchy to absorb the impact of flying insects. The spider dangles from a third type that&#39;s as tough as steel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How and why silks behave in these various ways is a puzzle, but the secret likely lies in genes. Finding those genes, though, isn&#39;t easy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Until recently, scientists had to first chop the glands&#39; DNA into pieces and have a computer try to put the sequence back together like a jigsaw puzzle. That&#39;s a daunting task, and it&#39;s especially difficult for spiders, because their genes are very long and repetitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s as if the sentence &quot;The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog&quot; is instead, &quot;The quick brown fox jumps, jumps, jumps, jumps, jumps, jumps, jumps, jumps over the lazy dog,&quot; said Sarah Stellwagen from the University of Maryland, Baltimore County. If you have no idea what the sentence says and have to rebuild it from a shredded mess of thousands of copies, how do you know how many &quot;jumps&quot; to put into it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&#39;s the problem Stellwagen faced when she recently determined the entire set of genes, and their DNA makeup, for spider silk glue. She&#39;d thought she could do it fairly quickly, but it took almost two years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scientists have to recover the full gene to truly mimic natural silk, she said. If they try to produce synthetic silk from just part of a gene or some lab-built stunted version, &quot;it&#39;s not as good as what a spider makes,&quot; Stellwagen said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&#39;s the issue researchers and companies have had in the past using genetically modified yeast, microbes and even goats to make synthetic silk. Only last year did a group make a small amount that perfectly mimicked an orb-weaving spider&#39;s dragline silk, the type it dangles from, using bacteria.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But that was only one type of silk from one species. Hayashi asked: &quot;What about the other 48,000?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Technology has improved. Researchers can now determine genes from beginning to end without first chopping them up. And companies have gotten ever closer to mass-produced synthetic silks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, it&#39;s a matter of uncovering the secrets of the potentially thousands of other silks out there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a hard task, considering the many spiders she has yet to study and that some are about the size of the period at the end of this sentence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;But hey, you know, we all have goals,&quot; she said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By JEREMY REHMNEW YORK</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>source:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://japantoday.com/category/tech/library-of-spider-silk-could-hold-secrets-for-new-materials\">https://japantoday.com/category/tech/library-of-spider-silk-could-hold-secrets-for-new-materials</a></p>', 'japantoday1.jpg', '2019-08-19 11:03:38', b'1', 3, b'1'),
(77, 'Fujitsu initiates year-round recruitment', 'Fujitsu has announced that it will move to further develop the existing recruitment framework for new graduates, eliminating the application period for the recruitment process that normally ends in August every year. Year-round recruitment will commence for university and graduate students in their final year and for those that have already graduated.', 'GeeksJapan', 'Work', 'live in japan, work in japan, it engineer, artificial intelligence, japan, tokyo', '<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>TOKYO</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fujitsu has announced that it will move to further develop the existing recruitment framework for new graduates, eliminating the application period for the recruitment process that normally ends in August every year. Year-round recruitment will commence for university and graduate students in their final year and for those that have already graduated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By conducting year-round recruitment, Fujitsu said it aims to further expand opportunities for acquiring diverse talent both in Japan and overseas. Through its efforts to enable job hunting that grants prospective employees a high degree of freedom that matches their personal values, Fujitsu said it hopes this will ensure sufficient time for learning experiences and opportunities to further personal growth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fujitsu conducts fair and impartial recruitment activities in accordance with the &quot;Guidelines for Recruitment and Selection&quot; issued by the Nippon Keidanren (Japan Business Federation). Recruitment activities for new employees from fiscal 2021 onward will also be conducted in accordance with the guidelines set by the Japanese government.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>source:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://japantoday.com/category/business/fujitsu-initiates-year-round-recruitment\">https://japantoday.com/category/business/fujitsu-initiates-year-round-recruitment</a></p>', 'fujitisu.jpg', '2019-08-19 11:15:07', b'1', 4, b'1');
